op 50]] Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|title= Rapports annuels 1995 |publisher= [[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= 10 June 2016 |url= http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=1995 |language= fr}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|43\n|-\n|Canada Dance/Urban (''[[Canadian dance chart|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title= RPM Top 50 Dance Tracks of 1995 |magazine= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |volume= 62 |issue= 20 |date= 18 December 1995 |accessdate= 12 December 2019 |url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.2842&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.2842.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.2842}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|26\n|-\n|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles|Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Year End Sales Charts: Eurochart Hot 100 Singles 1995 |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |page= 14 |volume= 12 |issue= 51/52 |date= 23 December 1995 |accessdate= 2 December 2019 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1995/MM-1995-12-23.pdf}}</ref> \n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Classement Singles \u2013 ann\u00e9e 1995 |website= Disque en France |url= http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259376&year=1995 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120307201551/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259376&year=1995 |archivedate= 7 March 2012 |language= fr}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jahrescharts \u2013 1995 |publisher= Offiziellecharts.de. GfK Entertainment Charts |url= https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1995 |archivedate= 17 March 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160317151305/https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1995 |language= de}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|51\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaarlijsten 1995 |publisher= Stichting Nederlandse Top 40 |accessdate= 3 December 2019 |url= https://www.top40web.nl/jaarlijsten/jr1995.html |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|130\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Single Top 100]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1995 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= 10 June 2016 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1995&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|99\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ]])<ref>{{cite web|title= End of Year Charts 1995 |publisher= Recorded Music New Zealand |accessdate= 10 June 2016 |url= http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3884}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19950101&newi=0&mode=list&navi=no&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE |title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 1995 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150403111118/http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19950101&newi=0&mode=list&navi=no&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE |archivedate= 3 April 2015}}. Hitlistan.se.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|Switzerland ([[Swiss Hitparade|Schweizer Hitparade]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Schweizer Jahreshitparade 1995 |website= Hitparade.ch. |url= http://hitparade.ch/year.asp?key=1995 |accessdate= 8 December 2019 |language= de}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|43\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK Singles]] (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Top 100 Singles 1995 |magazine= [[Music Week]] |page= 9 |date= 13 January 1996}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1996)\n!Position\n|-\n|Canada Dance/Urban (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title= RPM Year End Dance ~ Top 50 |magazine= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |volume= 64 |issue= 18 |date= 16 December 1996 |accessdate= 10 June 2016 |url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9738&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9738.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9738}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|}\n\n====Certifications====\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|artist=N-Trance|title=Stayin' Alive|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1995|certyear=1995|certref=<ref>{{cite web|title= 1995 ARIA Singles Chart |publisher= [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] |accessdate= 24 October 2018 |url= https://www.ariacharts.com.au/annual-charts/1995/singles-chart}}</ref>|accessdate=24 October 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|type=single|artist=N?Trance|title=Staying Alive|award=Gold|relyear=1995|certyear=1997|accessdate=12 November 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|type=single|artist=N-Trance|title=Stayin' Alive|award=Gold|relyear=1995|certyear=1995|accessdate=2 November 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=New Zealand|type=single|artist=N-Trance|title=Stayin' Alive|award=Platinum|relyear=1995|certyear=1995| id=3692|recent=website|accessdate=24 October 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=N-Trance|title=Stayin' Alive|award=Silver|relyear=1995|certyear=1995|accessdate=24 October 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Stayin' Alive (Serban Mix)==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Stayin' Alive (Serban Mix)\n| cover      = Bee Gees Staying Alive Serban mix.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bee Gees]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2017|2|10|df=y}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=57}}\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     =\n*[[Barry Gibb]]\n*[[Robin Gibb]]\n*[[Maurice Gibb]]\n| producer   = Bee Gees\n| prev_title = [[If I Can't Have You (Bee Gees song)|If I Can't Have You (The Disco Boys remixes)]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|type=single|{{YouTube|2FbFzIWGYWw|\"Stayin' Alive (Serban Mix) (Audio)\"}}}}\n}}\n\nOn 10 February 2017, [[Capitol Records]] released a new version of the song entitled \"'''Stayin' Alive\" (Serban mix)'''.<ref name=\"iTunes\"/> The song was mixed by Serban Ghenea from \"hi-resolution audio files\" from the original recording session of \"Stayin' Alive\", and it was mastered by [[Tom Coyne (music engineer)|Tom Coyne]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Stayin' Alive Remix |website= Beegees.com |accessdate= 14 February 2017 |url= http://www.beegees.com/new-staying-alive-mix-released/}}</ref> The single was released in commemoration of the 40th anniversary of the [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|''Saturday Night Fever'' (1977) soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Bee Gees : Serban remixe \"Stayin' Alive\" pour le 40e anniversaire de \"Saturday Night Fever\" |publisher= [[Universal Music Group]] |accessdate= 14 February 2017 |url= http://www.universalmusic.fr/4057-bee-gees-serban-remixe-stayin-alive-pour-le-40e-anniversaire-de-saturday-night-fever.html |language= fr}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n*Digital download<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|title= Stayin' Alive (Serban Mix) \u2013 Single |publisher= [[iTunes]] |accessdate= 14 February 2017 |url= https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/stayin-alive-serban-mix-single/id1202261274}}</ref>\n#\"Stayin' Alive (Serban mix)\" \u2013 4:57\n\n==Appearances in other media==In the BBC show ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', as a ringtone of [[Professor Moriarty|Jim Moriarty]], in its [[A Scandal in Belgravia|series two premiere]] on New Year's Day, 2012. It is also heard in the [[The Reichenbach Fall|series two finale]], when Moriarty tells Sherlock that their final problem is 'Stayin' Alive', whilst playing the song on his phone.<ref>{{cite news|first= Curt |last= Wagner |title= 'Sherlock' Season 2: Steven Moffat talks Holmes, Moriarty and 'Stayin' Alive' |newspaper= [[Chicago Tribune]] |date= 3 May 2012 |accessdate= 25 April 2017 |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-sherlock-season-2-steven-moffat-interview-tv-20120503-story.html}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one singles in Australia during the 1970s#1978|List of number-one singles in Australia during the 1970s]]\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 1978|List of ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles of 1978]]\n*[[List of Cash Box Top 100 number-one singles of 1978|List of ''Cash Box'' Top 100 number-one singles of 1978]]\n*[[List of Dutch Top 40 number-one singles of 1978]]\n*[[List of European number-one hits of 1978]]\n*[[List of number-one hits of 1978 (Italy)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1978 (Canada)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1978 (France)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles in 1978 (New Zealand)]]\n*[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://beegeesstayingalive.com Bee Gees Stayin' Alive Fansite]\n*{{MetroLyrics song|bee-gees|stayin-alive}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Saturday Night Fever soundtrack}}\n{{Bee Gees}}\n{{Bee Gees singles}}\n\n[[Category:1977 songs]]\n[[Category:1977 singles]]\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:All Around the World Productions singles]]\n[[Category:Bee Gees songs]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Disco songs]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Vocal Arrangement for Two or More Voices]]\n[[Category:Jo Stafford songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Bruce Gowers]]\n[[Category:Number-one dance singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Italy]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RSO Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Albhy Galuten]]\n[[Category:Songs from Saturday Night Fever]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Barry Gibb]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Maurice Gibb]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robin Gibb]]\n[[Category:N-Trance songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1977 song by the Bee Gees}}\n{{About|the Bee Gees song|other uses}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Stayin' Alive\n| cover      = Bee Gees Stayin Alive.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = UK 7-inch vinyl single\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bee Gees]]\n| album      = [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|Saturday Night Fever]]\n| B-side     = [[If I Can't Have You (Bee Gees song)|If I Can't Have You]]\n| released   = 13 December 1977\n| format     = [[Gramophone record#Formats|7-inch 45{{nbsp}}rpm record]]\n| recorded   = 1977\n| studio     = [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], H\u00e9rouville, France\n| genre      = [[Disco]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Jason |last= Ankeny |title= Stayin' Alive \u2013 review |website= [[AllMusic]] |url= http://www.allmusic.com:80/song/stayin-alive-mt0034983849 |archivedate= 3 November 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121103145507/http://www.allmusic.com/song/stayin-alive-mt0034983849 |url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Shmoop\">{{cite web|title= Stayin' Alive by the Bee Gees |publisher= Shmoop |url= http://www.shmoop.com/stayin-alive/music.html |accessdate= 14 February 2015}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:45\n| label      = [[RSO Records|RSO]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Barry Gibb]]|[[Robin Gibb]]|[[Maurice Gibb]]}}\n| producer   =\n*Bee Gees\n*[[Albhy Galuten]]\n*Karl Richardson\n| prev_title = [[How Deep Is Your Love (Bee Gees song)|How Deep Is Your Love]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Night Fever]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = StayinAlive.ogg\n | description = \"Stayin' Alive\"\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|fNFzfwLM72c|\"Stayin' Alive\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Stayin' Alive'''\" is a song written and performed by the [[Bee Gees]] from the [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|''Saturday Night Fever'' motion picture soundtrack]]. The song was released on 13 December 1977 as the second single from the ''Saturday Night Fever'' soundtrack. The band co-produced the song with [[Albhy Galuten]] and Karl Richardson. It is one of the Bee Gees' [[signature song]]s. In 2004, \"Stayin' Alive\" was placed at number 189 on the list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref name=\"RS\"/> In 2004, it ranked No. 9 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema. In a UK television poll on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in December 2011 it was voted fifth in \"''[[The Nation's Favourite|The Nation's Favourite Bee Gees Song]]''\".<ref>\"The Nation's Favourite Bee Gees Song\". [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. 9 December 2011.</ref>\n\nOn its release, \"Stayin' Alive\" climbed the charts to hit the number one spot on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] the week of 4 February 1978, remaining there for four consecutive weeks. In the process, it became one of the band's most recognisable tunes, in part because of its place at the beginning of ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]''. In the United States, it would become the second of six consecutive number-one singles, tying the record with [[the Beatles]] for most consecutive number ones in the United States at the time (a record broken by [[Whitney Houston]] who achieved seven consecutive number-ones).\n\n== Writing and recording ==\nThe [[Record producer|executive producer]] of the [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|''Saturday Night Fever'' motion picture soundtrack]] and future Bee Gees manager [[Robert Stigwood]] asked the band to write a few songs for the soundtrack. At this point, the film was in early stages and it did not have a title; in fact, all Stigwood had to go on was a ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' cover story about [[disco]]mania. \n\nThey wrote \"Stayin' Alive\" over the course of a few days while sprawled on the staircase at the [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]] studio near Paris. As with many other artists during the 1970s, the Bee Gees recorded a majority of the soundtrack in France for tax reasons.\n\n[[RSO Records]] wanted the song to share the then-title of the film, \"Saturday Night\", but the Bee Gees refused a title change, insisting that there had been too many songs with \"Saturday\" in the title, and the album already had a song with the word \"night\" in the title\u2014\"Night Fever\". Rather than change the name of the former song to match the film, Stigwood expanded the name of the film to encompass the title of the latter song. Over the years, the brothers have had mixed feelings about the song. On one hand, they admit it brought them tremendous fame; on the other, it led to their being pigeonholed as a disco act, despite a long and varied career before and after.<ref name=\"GB2\"/>\n\nSeveral words from [[Robin Gibb]]'s [[Concorde]] ticket inspired the Gibbs{{clarify|date=May 2016}} to write the lyrics for \"Stayin' Alive\". Robin recalls, \"The subject matter of 'Stayin' Alive' is actually quite a serious one; It's about survival in the streets of [[New York City|New York]], and the lyrics actually say that\". Barry Gibb also recalls, \"People crying out for help. Desperate songs. Those are the ones that become giants. The minute you capture that on record, it's gold. 'Stayin' Alive' is the epitome of that. Everybody struggles against the world, fighting all the bullshit and things that can drag you down. And it really is a victory just to survive. But when you climb back on top and win bigger than ever before, well that's something everybody reacts to everybody\".<ref name=\"everybody\">{{cite book|first= Andrew M\u00f4n |last= Hughes |title= The Bee Gees: Tales Of The Brothers Gibb |year= 2009 |publisher= [[Music Sales Group]] |url= https://books.google.com?id=KugbDQHX0R8C&pg=PT826 |isbn= 978-0-85712-004-5}}</ref> \"We'd also written a song called 'Saturday Night'\", Maurice explains, \"But there were so many songs called 'Saturday Night' even [[Saturday Night (Bay City Rollers song)|one]] by the [[Bay City Rollers]], so when we rewrote it for the movie, we called it 'Stayin' Alive'.<ref>{{cite book|first= Melinda |last= Bilyeu |first2= Hector |last2= Cook |first3= Andrew M\u00f4n |last3= Hughes |title= The Ultimate Biography of the Bee Gees: Tales Of The Brothers Gibb |publisher= Music Sales Group |year= 2013 |url= https://books.google.com?id=Uzv_AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT661 |isbn= 978-0-85712-004-5}}</ref>\n\nThe track was finished at [[Criteria Studios]], with [[Maurice Gibb]] laying down a bass line similar to the guitar riff, Barry Gibb and [[Alan Kendall]] on guitar riffs, and [[Blue Weaver]] adding synthesizers. The Boneroo Horns parts were added. Barry sings falsetto on the whole song, except on the line \"life\u2019s going nowhere, somebody help me\".<ref name=\"GB2\"/> \n\nDue to the death of backing drummer [[Dennis Bryon]]'s mother in the middle of the song's sessions, the group first looked for a replacement. The shortage of qualified drummers in the area prompted the group to try a [[drum machine]], but it did not offer satisfactory results.<ref name=\"Shmoop\"/> After listening to the drum track of the already-recorded \"[[Night Fever]]\", the group and producer Albhy Galuten took two bars from that track, rerecorded them as a recurrent loop on a separate tape, and proceeded with sessions for \"Stayin' Alive\". This accounts for the unchanging rhythm throughout the song. As a joke, the group listed the drummer as \"Bernard Lupe\" (a takeoff on session drummer [[Bernard Purdie]]). Mr. Lupe became a highly sought-after drummer\u2014until it was discovered that he did not exist.<ref name=\"GB2\">{{cite web|first= Joseph |last= Brennan |title= Gibb Songs: 1977 |url= http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/beegees/77.html |accessdate= 3 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlbhy Galuten talks about the recording of \"Stayin' Alive\":\n\n{{quote|Barry and I listened carefully to find a bar that felt really good. Everyone knows that it's more about feel than accuracy in drum tracks. We chose a bar that felt so good that we ended up using that same loop on 'Stayin' Alive,' and 'More Than a Woman,' and then again on Barbra Streisand's song 'Woman in Love.' To make the loop, we copied the drums onto one-quarter-inch tape. Karl spliced the tape and jury rigged it so that it was going over a mic stand and around a plastic reel. At first, we were doing it just as a temporary measure. As we started to lay tracks down to it, we found that it felt really great-very insistent but not machinelike. It had a human feel. By the time we had overdubbed all the parts to the songs and Dennis came back, there was no way we could get rid of the loop.<ref name=\"loop\">{{cite web|first= Mark |last= Small |title= Albhy Galuten tells his story |date= Summer 2002 |publisher= Brothersgibb.org |url= http://www.brothersgibb.org/reports-albhy-galuten.html |accessdate= 27 January 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nIn their work together, Gibb and Galuten had tried playing with a [[click track]] as Galuten explained:\n\n{{quote|While today's musicians know how to get a good groove with the click, back then, if you used a click track you rarely got a good feel. The loop crossed the boundary giving us music that was in time with a good feel. If I had been working for a technology company then and knew what I was doing, I would have tried to patent the idea. Nonetheless, it changed a lot of things. That first loop was a watershed event in our life and times.<ref name=\"loop\"/>}}\n\n==Release==\n{{Refimprove section|date=July 2017}}\nThe song was not initially scheduled for release, with \"[[How Deep Is Your Love (Bee Gees song)|How Deep Is Your Love]]\" selected as lead single, but fans called radio stations and [[RSO Records]] requesting the song immediately after seeing trailers for ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', featuring the track over the aforementioned introductory scene. The single was eventually released in mid-December, a month after the album, and moved to the top of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the United States in February, where it would stay for four weeks. Soon after, it would slide to number two, locking in a solid one-two punch with the Bee Gees's third smash hit from the album, \"Night Fever\". In the United Kingdom, \"Stayin' Alive\" was not as popular as it was in the United States, but was still a huge hit, topping out at number four.\n\nFurther demonstrating the Bee Gees's US chart domination in 1978, \"Stayin' Alive\" was replaced at number one with the group's younger brother [[Andy Gibb]]'s single, \"[[(Love Is) Thicker Than Water|Love Is Thicker Than Water]]\", followed by the Bee Gees's \"Night Fever\" for their longest run, seven weeks. This was then replaced by [[Yvonne Elliman]]'s \"[[If I Can't Have You (Bee Gees song)|If I Can't Have You]]\". [[Barry Gibb]] had a hand in writing all four of these songs, becoming the only person in history to write four successive US number-one singles. Besides the version that appeared on the soundtrack album and the edited 45RPM single for Top 40 radio release, there was yet another version, from the same recording session but of a slightly different mix, that was distributed on twelve-inch vinyl to club DJs and radio stations that specialised in airing longer versions of hit songs. This \"Special Disco Version\", as it was called, featured all the same parts as the album version but had a horn rhythm section part interjected twice. Although twelve-inch \"Disco Versions\" were usually sped up, this version was slowed down slightly. This version was finally released on CD when Reprise re-issued ''[[Bee Gees Greatest]]'' in 2007 in an expanded and remastered edition. As for the message of the song, Robin Gibb was quoted as saying, \"'Stayin' Alive' is about survival in the big city\u2014any big city\u2014but especially New York.\" The longest version of \"Stayin' Alive\" ever made was faded at 6:59, and that version was finally released on the remastered version of ''[[Bee Gees Greatest]]''. The album edit is a still generous 4:43, but it was down to 3:29 for the single version.<ref name=\"GB2\"/>\n\nInitial plans were for [[Yvonne Elliman]], then known for ballads, to record \"[[How Deep Is Your Love (Bee Gees song)|How Deep Is Your Love]]\" for ''Saturday Night Fever'', while the Bee Gees produced their own version of the more disco-oriented \"If I Can't Have You\" for the film. Robert Stigwood thought he would prefer the songs from different genders and directed the group to cut the ballad, while Elliman cut \"If I Can't Have You\" with her usual producer [[Freddie Perren]]. Satisfied with this switch, Elliman's interpretation made the soundtrack, while the Bee Gees's version was relegated to the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] of the \"Stayin' Alive\" single. The brothers' version has since appeared on CD in hits compilations.\n\n[[George Martin]] commented about this song saying: \"The great thing about 'Stayin' Alive' is that it had a great [[guitar]] hook to start with which set up the theme, that pulsating beat. It's no coincidence, by the way, that the disco beat of 120 beats per minute coincides the heartbeat of your heart when you're excited. This was a key thing which underlined the whole tune, and when the vocals came in, the vocals were so designed that they pushed that beat further\".<ref name=\"everybody\"/>\n\n===Music video===\nThe music video for the song is of an entirely different concept from ''Saturday Night Fever''. It was filmed on [[Sony Pictures Studios|MGM Studios]]'s backlot #2 in [[Culver City, California]]. The group was filming the movie, ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' on the lot at the same time. The video featured Quality Street\u2014a set that was used for such films as ''[[The Three Musketeers (1948 film)|The Three Musketeers]]'' and ''[[Young Frankenstein]]''\u2014as well as the Grand Central Station set used in the films ''[[The Band Wagon]]'' and the opening of ''[[That's Entertainment!]]'' with [[Fred Astaire]].<ref>{{cite book|first= Steven |last= Bingen |year= 2011 |title= MGM: Hollywood's Greatest Backlot |isbn= 9781595808936 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pKePBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover}}</ref> As the group walks past one of the railway cars in the video, the words \"New York Central\" can be seen printed on the side of the train above a passenger window. The MGM art directors added this bit of authenticity because the actual [[New York Central Railroad]] operated several lines from [[Grand Central Terminal]] in [[New York City]] during the 20th century until 1969.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Streamline Steam Engine Attains High Speed |date= February 1935 |page= 211 |magazine= [[Popular Mechanics]] |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=yN8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA211}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Barry Gibb]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead]], [[Backing vocalist|harmony]] and backing vocals, [[rhythm guitar]]\n*[[Robin Gibb]] \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n*[[Maurice Gibb]] \u2013 harmony and backing vocals, [[Bass guitar|bass]]\n*[[Alan Kendall]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n*[[Dennis Bryon]] (Bernard Lupe) \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n*[[Blue Weaver]] \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[synthesizer]]\n*[[Joe Lala]] \u2013 [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n\n==Track listing==\n*\"Stayin' Alive\" \u2013 3:29\n*\"If I Can't Have You\" \u2013 3:25\n\n===1989 reissue===\n*\"Subway\" \u2013 4:20\n*\"Love So Right\" \u2013 3:33\n\n==Use in medical training==\n\"Stayin' Alive\" was used in a study to train medical professionals to provide the correct number of chest compressions per minute while performing [[cardiopulmonary resuscitation|CPR]]. The song has close to 104 [[tempo|beats per minute]], and 100\u2013120 chest compressions per minute are recommended by the [[British Heart Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bhf.org.uk/heart-health/life-saving-skills/hands-only-cpr-faqs.aspx |title= Hands-Only CPR FAQs |publisher= [[British Heart Foundation]] |accessdate= 8 January 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120110213223/http://www.bhf.org.uk/heart-health/life-saving-skills/hands-only-cpr-faqs.aspx |archivedate= 10 January 2012}}</ref> and endorsed by the [[Resuscitation Council (UK)]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.resus.org.uk/siteindx.htm |title= Resuscitation Council (UK) |publisher= [[Resuscitation Council (UK)]] |accessdate= 8 January 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120114012255/http://www.resus.org.uk/SiteIndx.htm |archivedate= 14 January 2012}}</ref> A study on medical professionals found that the quality of CPR is better when thinking about \"Stayin' Alive\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Scott |last= Simon |date= 25 October 2008 |title= Another Use For 'Stayin' Alive': Staying Alive |publisher= [[NPR]] |accessdate= 22 May 2010 |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96134166}}</ref> This was parodied in the Season 5 episode of comedy series ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' \"[[Stress Relief (The Office)|Stress Relief]]\"<ref>{{cite news|first= Kelly |last= West |title= TV Recap: The Office \u2013 Stress Relief |website= Cinema Blend |date= 1 February 2009 |accessdate= 30 October 2017 |url= https://www.cinemablend.com/television/TV-Recap-Office-Stress-Relief-14947.html}}</ref> and the song itself was used in a [[Grey's Anatomy (season 11)|season 11 episode]] of the medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first= Ariana |last= Bacle |title= 'Grey's Anatomy' recap: 'I Feel the Earth Move' |magazine= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= 14 March 2015 |accessdate= 30 October 2017 |url= http://ew.com/recap/greys-anatomy-season-11-episode-15/2/}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2011, the song was featured in a Hands Only CPR PSA campaign video from the [[American Heart Association]] and featured actor and medical doctor [[Ken Jeong]] in the classic [[John Travolta]] outfit from ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first= Jaimie Dalessio |last= Clayton |title= Stayin' Alive With Hands-Only CPR |publisher= [[Everyday Health]] |date= 6 June 2012 |accessdate= 30 October 2017 |url= https://www.everydayhealth.com/heart-health/0606/hands-only-cpr-keeps-people-stayin-alive.aspx}}</ref> [[Vinnie Jones]] stars in the British version of this CPR video in association with the [[British Heart Foundation]] shown on TV in January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Radnedge|first1=Aidan|title=Vinnie Jones shows how to perform CPR to the sound of Stayin' Alive|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/01/03/vinnie-jones-shows-how-to-perform-cpr-to-the-sound-of-stayin-alive-272283/|accessdate=30 October 2017|work=Metro|date=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Publisher\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Rank\n|-\n|1981\n|[[Dave Marsh]] & James Bernard\n|United States\n|\"Singles Of The Year 1978\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Book Of Rock Lists \u2013 Singles Of The Year.. 1978 |publisher= Rocklist.net |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/dmsingles_72_80.htm#78}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n|1989\n|[[Dave Marsh]]\n|United States\n|\"The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever Made\"<ref>[[Dave Marsh|Marsh, Dave]]. {{cite web|url= http://www.control.lth.se/~anton/personal/music/1001_number.html |title= The 1001 Greatest Singles, by Number |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20020204203107/http://www.control.lth.se/~anton/personal/music/1001_number.html |archivedate= 4 February 2002}}. Control.lth.se.</ref>\n|716\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 100 Best Singles Of The Last 25 Years\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Rolling Stone \u2013 The 100 Best Singles Of The Last 25 Years |work= [[Rolling Stone]] |url= http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/rstone.html#singles |publisher= Rocklist.net |date= 20 August 2006 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n|50\n|-\n|1995\n|[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n|United States\n|\"500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://rockhall.com/exhibits/one-hit-wonders-songs-that-shaped-rock-and-roll/ |title= Experience The Music: One Hit Wonders and The Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll |publisher= [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum]] |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2000\n|''Rolling Stone''\n|United States\n|\"100 Greatest Pop Songs\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Rolling Stone\u2019s 100 Greatest Pop Songs |work= Rolling Stone |publisher= Rocklist.net |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/rs200.html#100%20Greatest%20Pop%20Songs |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110105063902/http://rocklistmusic.co.uk/rs200.html |archivedate= 5 January 2011}}</ref>\n|93\n|-\n|2000\n|[[VH1]]\n|United States\n|\"100 Greatest Dance Songs\"<ref>{{cite web|title= VH1: 100 Greatest Dance Songs |publisher= [[VH1]]. Rock On The Net |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1dance.htm}}</ref>\n|10\n|-\n|2001\n|[[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA)\n|United States\n|\"Songs of the Century\" (365)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/ |title= Songs of the Century |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20051211164530/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/ |archivedate= 11 December 2005}}. [[CNN]]. 7 March 2001.</ref>\n|94\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[PopMatters]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 100 Best Songs Since Johnny Rotten Roared\"<ref>Horning, Rob {{cite web|url= http://popmatters.com/music/top100songs/1977-2003-61-70.shtml |title= 100 From 1977 \u2013 2003: The 100 Best Songs Since Johnny Rotten Roared > 61 \u2013 70 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030824054058/http://popmatters.com/music/top100songs/1977-2003-61-70.shtml |archivedate= 24 August 2003}}. ''[[PopMatters]]''.</ref>\n|65\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n|United Kingdom\n|\"100 Songs That Changed The World\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Q \u2013 100 Songs That Changed The World |work= [[Q (magazine)|Q]] |publisher= Rocklist.net |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage2.html#100%20Songs%20That%20Changed%20The%20World}}</ref>\n|17\n|-\n|2003\n|''Q''\n|United Kingdom\n|\"The 1001 Best Songs Ever\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Q Special Edition - 1001 Best Songs Ever.. |work= Q |publisher= Rocklist.net |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/q1001_songs.htm}}</ref>\n|280\n|-\n|2004\n|''Rolling Stone''\n|United States\n|\"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\"<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/2 |title= The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time (1-500) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114448/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/2 |archivedate= 20 August 2006}}. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref>\n|189\n|-\n|2004\n|[[American Film Institute|AFI]]\n|United States\n|\"[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs100.pdf |title= AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110313151657/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs100.pdf |archivedate= 13 March 2011}}. [[American Film Institute]].</ref>\n|9\n|-\n\n|2009\n|[[VH1]]\n|United States\n|\"100 Greatest Rock Songs\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |title= It's Only A Riff, But We Like It |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090408042358/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |archivedate= 8 April 2009}}. [[VH1]]. [[Viacom Media Networks|MTV Networks]].</ref>\n|54\n|-\n|2010\n|''Rolling Stone''\n|United States\n|\"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= 500 Greatest Songs of All Time: Bee Gees, 'Stayin' Alive' |magazine= Rolling Stone |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/bee-gees-stayin-alive-20110526 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n|191\n|-\n|2011\n|Robert Dimery\n|United Kingdom\n|\"1001 Songs You Must Hear Before You Die\"<ref>{{cite book|title= 1001 Songs You Must Hear Before You Die |first= Robert |last= Dimery |publisher= [[Lagard\u00e8re Publishing|Octopus Publishing Group]] |year= 2011 |url= https://books.google.com/books/?id=UH_EOUR4tmkC&pg=PT2497 |isbn= 978-1-8440-3717-9}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n|United States\n|\"All-TIME 100 Songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= All-TIME 100 Songs: 'Stayin' Alive' |magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |url= http://entertainment.time.com/2011/10/24/the-all-time-100-songs/slide/stayin-alive-bee-gees/}}</ref>\n|*\n|}\n\n<small>(*) indicates the list is unordered.</small>\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1978)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Australia No. 1 hits -- 1970's |website= World Charts |accessdate= 10 June 2013 |url= http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus70.htm |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140424142031/http://www.worldcharts.