st=Lincoln|first=Ross A.|date=October 2, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[7th_Streamy_Awards|7th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"7thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/2017/09/winners-announced-for-the-7th-annual-streamy-awards/|title=2016 Winners Announced for the 7th Annual Streamy Awards|last=Brown|first=Kelsey|date=September 26, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"7thstreamys2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/7th-annual-nominees/|title=7th Annual Nominees|language=en-US|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[8th_Streamy_Awards|8th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref name=\"8thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/8th-annual-nominees/|title=8th Annual Nominees & Winners|language=en-US|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"8thstreamys\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|News\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[9th_Streamy_Awards|9th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref name=\"9thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/2019/12/winners-announced-for-the-9th-annual-streamy-awards/|title=Winners Announced for the 9th Annual Streamy Awards|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"9thstreamys\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Viral marketing]]\n* ''[[BlackBoxTV Presents]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Defranco, Philip}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century atheists]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the online media industry]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American media company founders]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:East Carolina University alumni]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Maker Studios people]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:SourceFed people]]\n[[Category:Streamy Award winners]]\n[[Category:University of South Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:Video bloggers]]\n[[Category:Video game commentators]]\n[[Category:Male bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Missing information|date=November 2019|DeFranco's career post-2017|talk=Career 2017-present missing from article}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name = Philip DeFranco \n| image = Philip Defranco.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = DeFranco in 2018\n| alt = \n| birth_name = Philip James Franchini Jr.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|12|1}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->\n| nationality = American\n| residence = [[Encino, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*YouTube personality\n*entrepreneur}}\n| origin = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Lindsay Doty|March 7, 2015}}\n| signature = \n| website = {{flatlist|\n* https://www.roguerocket.com}}\n| channels = {{flatlist|\n* [https://www.youtube.com/philipdefranco PhilipDeFranco]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/phillyd PhillyD]}}\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n*News\n*Current events\n*Vlogging\n}}\n| subscribers = 6.4 million (Philip DeFranco)<br />1.22 million (Philly D)\n| views = 2.79 billion (Philip DeFranco)<br />257 million (Philly D)\n| network = Philip DeFranco Network & Merchandise<br />([[Discovery Digital Networks]]) (2012\u20132017) <br />\nRogue Rocket (2017\u2013present)\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* ''[[SourceFed]]''\n}}\n|catchphrase(s)=\n2008\u20132011 \"Oh, didn't see you there!\"\n\n2011\u20132016 \"'Sup Nation!\"\n\n2016\u2013present \"'Sup you beautiful bastards!\"\n\n| silver_button = yes \n| silver_year = 2008 \n| gold_button = yes\n| gold_year = 2010 \n}}\n\n'''Philip James''' '''DeFranco'''<ref name=Franchini>{{Citation|first=Philip|last=DeFranco|title=This is a Secret I've Had for 10 Years. It's time you know\u2026|date=August 20, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qcCcl9j8ojk|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> (born '''Philip James Franchini Jr.''';<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.facebook.com/DeFrancoNation/posts/10151105515124407 | title = Also for the 3 of... | last = DeFranco | first = Philip | date = August 28, 2012 | work = Facebook | accessdate =November 23, 2012 | quote = DeFranco is what I started telling people when they kept butchering my real last name which is Franchini pronounced Fran-keeny.}}</ref> born December 1, 1985), sometimes known online as '''PhillyD''' or '''sXePhil''', is a news commentator and an [[United States of America|American]] [[list of YouTube celebrities|YouTube personality]]. He is best known for ''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]'', a news commentary show centered on current events in politics and [[pop culture]] that has a playlist of over 1,000 videos since 2014 as well as his growing news network, Rogue Rocket.\n\nDeFranco has also been involved in the creation of other successful channels on YouTube, including [[Blog|personal vlog]] channel ''Philly D'', [[YouTube Original Channel Initiative|Google-funded]] news channel ''Sourcefed'', gaming channel ''Super Panic Frenzy'', and family vlog channel ''TheDeFrancoFam.'' His network of channels has over two billion views, and over six million total subscribers, with his primary channel having accumulated over 6.4 million subscribers and 2.7 billion views, as of January 2020. Over his decade-long YouTube career, he has won various awards for his achievements in online content.\n\nSince regaining control over his properties from the Discovery Network in May 2017, DeFranco has been working towards building the Rogue Rocket network in order to broaden his content.<ref name=\"DeFranco2017\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b7frDFkW05k|title=It's Time For You To Know...|date=May 1, 2017|last=DeFranco|first=Philip|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=Philip DeFranco}}</ref> On April 22, 2019, the Rogue Rocket website was launched.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALiRJpm5-QU</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDeFranco was born Philip James Franchini Jr. in [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"Franchini\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.phillyd.tv/about/ | title = About PhillyD.tv | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090412080902/http://www.phillyd.tv/about/ | archivedate = April 12, 2009 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=FBabout>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheRealDeFranco/about|title=Philip DeFranco about|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> He has a stepmother who works at a car dealership.<ref>{{cite video | people=DeFranco, Philip | date=January 31, 2012 | title=Whats New, PKD, and Things n Stuff | quote= my stepmum for the longest time ever to come out here for .. she works for a car dealership}}</ref> He is of Italian descent.<ref>{{cite web|last=DeFranco|first=Philip|url=https://www.facebook.com/DeFrancoNation/posts/10151105515124407|title=Also for the 3 of you freaking out that my real last name isn't DeFranco; it essentially is.|work=Philip DeFranco|publisher=Facebook|date=August 28, 2012|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a student at the [[University of South Florida]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/09/AR2007090901641.html | work=The Washington Post | title=YouTubers Try a Different Forum: Real Life | date=September 10, 2007}}</ref> a biology student at [[Asheville\u2013Buncombe Technical Community College]],<ref name=\"baltisun2\">{{cite news | title = For 1 college video blogger, it's a really strange trip | first = Andrew | last = Ratner | url = http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-09-23/news/0709220310_1_youtube-video-bloggers | newspaper = [[The Baltimore Sun]] | date = September 23, 2007 | accessdate = March 24, 2012 | archiveurl = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1341142571.html?dids=1341142571:1341142571&FMT=ABS | archivedate = September 23, 2007 | url-status = live | ref = sunfranchina}}</ref><ref name=\"oldmyspace\">{{cite web |last=DeFranco |first=Philip |url=//www.myspace.com/sxephil |title=sXePhil \u2013 MySpace |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219221637/http://www.myspace.com/sxephil |archivedate=February 19, 2007 |accessdate=January 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and later a junior at [[East Carolina University]].<ref name=\"Philip DeFranco is sxephil\" /> In 2007, Phil was living in [[Tampa, Florida]], and later [[Atlanta]], Georgia.<ref name=\"Philip DeFranco is sxephil\" /> He also worked as a [[waiting staff|waiter]] in a number of restaurants while making videos in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.phillyd.tv/home/ | title = Cool Stuff: Filed Under (Uncategorized) |author= Philly D. (sXePhil) |date= July 3, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715011103/http://www.phillyd.tv/home/ |website=PhillyD.tv| archivedate= July 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDeFranco lived in a car until moving back with his father in Tampa, Florida, on condition that he would return to college, which he ultimately did not do.<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite news|last=Chmielewski|first=Dawn C.|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-youtube-news-philip-defranco-elections-hub-20120828,0,4409102.story|title=YouTube gives wacky anchorman Philip DeFranco greater exposure|work=Los Angeles Times|date= August 28, 2012| accessdate= August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==YouTube==\n\n===Early years (2007\u20132011)===\n{{Further|The Philip DeFranco Show}}\n[[File:YouTube Partner Meet-Up VidCon2010a.jpg|thumb|300px|left|DeFranco (holding mic) at VidCon 2010]]\n\nDeFranco began his YouTube career during his finals at [[East Carolina University]] when he created his YouTube channel, calling it ''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]] (registered as sxephil)'', in which he talks about \"newsie type stuff, and things that matter to [him] today.\"<ref name=LATimes1/><ref>{{cite web|last=Eigenheer|first=Michelle|url=http://www.louisvillecardinal.com/2012/09/webshows-smarter/|title=Webshows that make you smarter|publisher=The Louisville Cardinal|date=September 11, 2012|accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[YouTube|YouTube partner program]] was available, he asked for donations from his viewers after claiming to have run out of money, and selling everything except his [[Macintosh|Mac]], camera, and clothes, and overdrawing his bank account so he could spend a night in a hotel as he found it too scary sleeping in a car in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"archivedphildottvsite\">{{cite web | url = http://www.phillyd.tv/home/ | title = PhillyD.tv | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612222246/http://www.phillyd.tv/home/ | archivedate=June 12, 2007 | accessdate = July 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAn online viewer census from 2007 showed that one-third of his viewers were 16- and 17-year-old girls.<ref name=\"baltisun1\">{{cite news | title = For 1 college video blogger, it's a really strange trip | first = Andrew | last = Ratner | url = http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-09-23/news/0709220310_1_youtube-video-bloggers | newspaper = The Baltimore Sun | date = September 23, 2007 | accessdate = March 24, 2012 | archiveurl = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1341142571.html?dids=1341142571:1341142571&FMT=ABS | archivedate = September 23, 2007 | url-status = live | ref = sunfranchina}}</ref> In the same year, DeFranco opened his second [[YouTube]] channel, \"''PhilipDeFranco''\", which includes a series of vlogs which he calls \"[[The Philip DeFranco Show|The Vloggity]]\".<ref name=vloggity>{{cite web|last=Trachtenberg|first=Lance|url=http://archive.placevine.com/blog/2012/06/01/the-vloggity-intelligent-venting/|title=The Vloggity: Intelligent Venting|publisher=Placevine|date=June 1, 2012|accessdate=March 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2007, DeFranco conducted an experiment by uploading a video titled \"[[Clickbait|Big Boobs and You]]\". The video's thumbnail image was what the title described, except that the image only flashed for a split second. The rest of the video's content was DeFranco talking. It quickly became his most successful video at the time, with 1.8 million views. From then on he changed his content to [[sex]], [[gossip]], and [[news]].<ref name=\"latimesthumbs\">{{cite news | title = The bait is sexy; be prepared for a switch | first = David | last = Sarno | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/14/entertainment/ca-webscout14 | newspaper = Los Angeles Times | date = October 14, 2007 | accessdate = November 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDeFranco used his large audience to win the [[Spore Creature Creator]], a game promotion competition, and in doing so beat celebrities such as [[Stan Lee]], [[Katy Perry]], and [[Elijah Wood]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Terdiman|first=Daniel|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/celebrities-get-their-chance-to-make-spore-creatures/|title=Celebrities get their chance to make 'Spore' creatures|website=CNET|date=September 2, 2008|accessdate=April 6, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406234658/http://www.cnet.com/news/celebrities-get-their-chance-to-make-spore-creatures/|archivedate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> The winner's prize was to choose which charity would receive a donation of $15,000. He chose the PKD Foundation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pkdcure.org/|title=Polycystic kidney disease {{!}} PKD Foundation|website=PKD Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2017}}</ref> an organization dedicated to fighting [[polycystic kidney disease]] (PKD), which he attributed to his family's history with the condition.<ref name=\"Philip DeFranco is sxephil\">{{cite news|url=http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Philip+DeFranco+is+sxephil/|title=Philip DeFranco is sxephil|date=January 2, 2009|publisher=Suicide Girls|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> DeFranco's large online audience also enabled him to win ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''{{'}}s Sexiest Geek of 2008 competition, a [[Open access poll|reader voted]] contest.<ref name=Wallace08>{{cite magazine|last=Wallace|first=Lewis|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/12/sexiest-geeks-o/|title=Sexiest Geeks of 2008, as Voted by Wired.com Readers|magazine=Wired|date=December 31, 2008|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he claimed in an interview to have a salary of over $250,000 from a number of sources on the internet, not just YouTube, but later denied it in several videos.<ref name=\"Philip DeFranco is sxephil\"/> In February 2012, DeFranco claimed he paid himself $100,000 a year, and reinvests the rest back into his company.<ref name=\"tfpay1\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Zeplin|first=Philip|url=http://novelconcept.org/how-much-money-does-youtubers-make/NovelConcept|title=How much money does YouTubers make?|publisher=Novel Concept|date=July 2, 2013|accessdate=January 7, 2014}}</ref> He has been paid by companies to create videos to promote [[Carl's Jr.]]'s burgers,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/24/online-video-ads-cmo-network-videoads.html | work=Forbes | first=Laurie | last=Burkitt | title=Brands Flock to Niche Video Networks | date=August 24, 2009}}</ref> and the US television series ''[[Lie to Me]]'' and ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hitviews-tapped-by-fox-to-market-fringe-and-lie-to-me-62093072.html|title=Hitviews Tapped by FOX to Market 'Fringe' and 'Lie to Me'|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDeFranco was a founding member of [[The Station (YouTube)|''The Station'']], but left only a few months after it was created.<ref name=\"tfpay1\">{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Joshua|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2012/02/10/phil-defranco-pays-himself-100k-a-year/|title=Phil DeFranco Pays Himself $100K a Year|publisher=Tubefilter|date=February 10, 2012|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> DeFranco also launched ''Like Totally Awesome'' (''LTA''), in which video reviews submitted by viewers are compiled into a single video. Reviews submitted cover movies, video games, and technology.<ref name=LTA>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|url=http://gigaom.com/video/philip-defranco-brings-together-aspiring-youtubers-for-like-totally-awesome/|title=Philip DeFranco Brings Together Aspiring YouTubers for Like Totally Awesome|publisher=GigaOM|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> The show was run by [[Sarah Penna]], the creator of the YouTube [[multi-channel network]] Big Frame.<ref>{{cite web|last=E\u00f6rd\u00f6gh|first=Fruzsina|url=http://readwrite.com/2012/07/18/sarah-penna-the-most-influential-new-media-entrepreneur-youve-never-heard-of#awesm=~otmiCpgc7d5vRJ|title=Sarah Penna: The Most Influential New Media Entrepreneur You've Never Heard Of|publisher=ReadWrite|date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=January 18, 2014}}</ref> Early in his YouTube career, Penna aided DeFranco, securing him coverage in news articles and magazines, such as ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]''. ''[[Mekanism]]'', an [[advertising agency]], was hired to promote him.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Laporte|first=Nicole|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3007141/digital-hollywood/how-digital-agent-sarah-penna-makes-hollywood-and-youtube-click|title=How Digital Agent Sarah Penna Makes Hollywood and YouTube Click|magazine=Fast Company|date=March 18, 2013|accessdate=January 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Borden|first=Mark|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1615327/mekanism-guarantee-they-engineer-virality|title=The Mekanism Guarantee: They Engineer Virality|magazine=Fast Company|date=May 1, 2010|accessdate=January 18, 2014}}</ref> In July 2010, along with [[Toby Turner]], DeFranco co-created ''CuteWinFail'', an online series which has been described by one ''[[ReadWrite]]'' writer as \"essentially the YouTube equivalent of America's Funniest Home Videos.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=E\u00f6rd\u00f6gh|first=Fruzsina|url=http://readwrite.com/2012/12/06/web-celebrity-toby-turner-fired-from-own-show-has-youtube-gone-corporate|title=Web Celebrity Toby Turner Fired From His Own Show: Has YouTube Gone Corporate?|publisher=ReadWrite|date=December 6, 2012|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====''Hooking Up''====\nIn October 2008, DeFranco co-starred with [[Jessica Lee Rose|Jessica Rose]] and [[Kevjumba|Kevin Wu]] in ''Hooking Up,'' written and acted by Woody Tondorf as a promo from HBOLabs (the online arm of [[HBO]]). ''Hooking Up'' is a scripted 10-episode Web-based series set at a fictional university where the students spend most of their time emailing and using [[Facebook]], but still manage to miscommunicate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2008/09/08/hbos-latest-experiment-hooking-up-youtube-stars-to-make-a-web-series/|title=HBO's Latest Experiment: 'Hooking Up' YouTube Stars To Make A Web Series|date=September 8, 2008|work=Tubefilter|access-date=March 5, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web |last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/televisionNews/idUSN0838976020080908 |title=HBO offshoot launches Web video series |website=Reuters|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=September 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nGuest appearances on ''Hooking Up'' have been made by [[Kevin Nalty]], [[Michael Buckley (Internet celebrity)|Michael Buckley]], and other popular Internet celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|last=Learmonth|first=Michael|url=http://www.alleyinsider.com/2008/9/looking-for-online-hit-hbo-tries-a-bunch-of-youtube-cewebrities |title=Looking For An Online Hit, HBO Tries A Bunch Of YouTube Cewebrities |publisher=Silicon Alley Insider|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=September 27, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912233609/http://www.alleyinsider.com/2008/9/looking-for-online-hit-hbo-tries-a-bunch-of-youtube-cewebrities|archivedate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBy the show's second day on YouTube, it had received more than 450,000 views.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigaom.com/2008/09/24/ntv-rerun-what-constitutes-an-online-hit/|title=NTV Rerun: What Constitutes an Online Hit?|publisher=GigaOM|date=September 24, 2008|accessdate=January 22, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Hooking Up: When YouTube stars get all cleaned up\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/webscout/2008/10/hooking-up.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502144131/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/webscout/2008/10/hooking-up.html|archivedate=May 2, 2009|title=Hooking Up: When YouTube stars get all cleaned up?|last=Russo|first=Maria|date=October 3, 2008|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 4, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bobbie Johnson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' said that many Web surfers have \"scoffed at what they see as a cynical attempt to cash in.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |first=Bobbie |last=Johnson |title=The rise and rise of the YouTube generation, and how adults can help |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/oct/06/youtube.youngpeople |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 6, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008 | location=London}}</ref>[[File:Philip DeFranco by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|DeFranco at VidCon 2012|alt=]]\n\n===Discovery/Group Nine years (2012\u20132017)===\nIn early 2012, DeFranco signed with [[Revision3]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Baldwin|first=Drew|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2012/01/06/philip-defranco-revision3/|title=Exclusive: Revision3 Exec On Signing Philip DeFranco|publisher=Tubefilter|date=January 6, 2012|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048175.html|title=Revision3 signs Philip DeFranco|magazine=Variety|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=HuffPost1>{{cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Evan|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/evan-shapiro/gangnam-style_b_1923147.html|title=We Have Watched 2,100 Years of 'Gangnam Style'|work=Huffington Post|date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref> Later in the year, DeFranco hosted the 25th anniversary of [[Discovery Channel]]'s [[Shark Week]].<ref name=HuffPost1/><ref name=MediaPost/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Holbrook|first=Damian|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Phil-DeFranco-Shark-Week-1052006.aspx|title=Phil DeFranco Bites Into Shark Week|magazine=TV Guide|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-guide/pay-tv-thursday-december-6-20121203-2aqyv.html |title = Pay TV: Thursday, December 6 |last = Newsome |first = Brad |date = December 6, 2012 | newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | accessdate = December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, it was reported that DeFranco received almost 30 million views a month.<ref name=MediaPost>{{cite web|last=Mahoney|first=Sarah|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/184115/can-one-tv-brand-reach-10-billion-devices.html|title=Can One TV Brand Reach 10 Billion Devices?|publisher=MediaPost|date=September 28, 2012|accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, DeFranco took part in a [[Google+]] Hangout with [[United States Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]] and [[Guy Kawasaki]], discussing [[Gun laws in the United States by state|gun laws]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Raghavan|first=Ramya|url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2013/01/fireside-hangouts-join-vice-president.html|title=Fireside Hangouts: Join Vice President Biden in a discussion about gun violence|publisher=Blogspot|work=Google Official Blog|date=January 23, 2013|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7LYlkknrku4</ref> DeFranco was a guest judge on the [[Internet Icon (season 2)|second season]] of ''[[Internet Icon]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lanning|first=Carly|url=http://newmediarockstars.com/2013/02/ryan-higa-talks-internet-icon-season-two-and-being-3-most-subscribed-on-youtube-interview/|title=Ryan Higa On 'Internet Icon' Season Two and Being YouTube's #3 Most Subscribed [INTERVIEW] |magazine=New Media Rockstars|date=February 12, 2013|accessdate=March 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, DeFranco's assets, including ''The Philip DeFranco Show'' and ''SourceFed'', were acquired by [[Revision3]], which itself was a subsidiary of [[Discovery Digital Networks]].<ref name=\"SpanglerMay13\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/discoverys-revision3-snaps-up-phil-defrancos-youtube-network-1200489614/|title=Discovery's Revision3 Snaps Up Phil DeFranco's YouTube Network|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=May 30, 2013|magazine=Variety|accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=WrapInterview>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|url=http://www.thewrap.com/media/article/phil-defranco-was-going-give-youtube-then-google-gave-him-money-107551|title=Phil DeFranco Was Ready to Give Up on YouTube \u2013 Until Google Gave Him Money|website=TheWrap|date=July 31, 2013|accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> Upon the acquisition, DeFranco became added as an exec of Revision3, the Senior VP of a new Revision3 subsidiary, Phil DeFranco Networks and Merchandise.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/05/30/revision3-philip-defranco-creative/|title=Revision3 Acquires Philip DeFranco's Assets, Adds DeFranco As Exec|publisher=Tubefilter|date=May 30, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Millar|first=DiAngelea|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/30/business/la-fi-ct-discovery-defranco-20130530|title=Philip DeFranco goes from Web host to network exec|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=May 30, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref> DeFranco spoke with Jon Erlichman about his partnership with [[Revision3]] following the deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/video/revision3-lands-philip-defranco-s-content-8G8xVic9Ts2npxz~OMWN9w.html|title=Revision3 Lands Philip DeFranco's Content|publisher=Bloomberg|date=May 31, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, as part of his new network, DeFranco launched another channel, ''ForHumanPeoples''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/10/09/philip-defranco-for-human-peoples-channel/|title=Philip DeFranco Debuts ForHumanPeoples Channel To Showcase Cool Stuff|publisher=Tubefilter|date=October 9, 2013|accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, DeFranco was a special guest in a live pre-show simulcast for the [[The Day of the Doctor|''Doctor Who'' 50th anniversary]] from YouTube Space LA.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Spangler|first=Todd|url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/bbc-america-slates-doctor-who-youtube-live-simulcast-to-promote-50th-anniversary-show-1200855484/|title=BBC America Slates 'Doctor Who' YouTube Live Simulcast to Promote 50th Anniversary Show|magazine=Variety|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> Additionally, DeFranco has organized live shows and meetup events in locations such as [[Arizona]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/08/07/phillyd-headed-to-phoenix-because-defranco-loves-dat-az/|title=Phil DeFranco Headed To Phoenix, Arizona For Live Show|publisher=Tubefilter|date=August 7, 2013|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2014/10/01/philip-defranco-does-la-vimeo-on-demand/|title=Vimeo On Demand Offers Philip DeFranco's Los Angeles Live Show|publisher=Tubefilter|date=October 1, 2014|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Garwol|first=Deanna|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/life-arts/a-fan-meets-her-favorite-youtube-star-20141023|title=A fan meets her favorite YouTube star|newspaper=The Buffalo News|date=October 23, 2014|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDeFranco aspired to have launched channels within his network by the end of 2013, though due to \"the logistical complications of joining Discovery, adding staff and strategizing the future,\" those plans did not materialize.<ref name=Shaw13/> DeFranco later planned 2014 to be the year that he would begin launching new channels.<ref name=Shaw13/> These plans once again fell through, but in 2015, DeFranco was involved in the launching of ''Super Panic Frenzy'', a gaming network, including a YouTube channel and a [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] live-stream show.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Molly|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2015/amazons-twitch-adding-discoverys-super-panic-frenzy-gaming-platform-monday/|title=Amazon's Twitch adding Discovery's 'Super Panic Frenzy' gaming platform Monday|work=GeekWire|date=March 20, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brouwer|first=Bree|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/03/16/discovery-digital-networks-super-panic-frenzy-defranco-suptic-scully/|title=Discovery Debuts Gaming Network Super Panic Frenzy, Hosts Launch Giveaway|publisher=Tubefilter|date=March 16, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Philip DeFranco (14531838135) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Defranco at VidCon 2014]]\nIn January 2012, DeFranco launched ''[[SourceFed]]'', which at the time was produced by James Haffner.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newton|first=Casey|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/techchron/2012/02/06/youtubes-phil-defranco-building-an-empire/|title=YouTube's Phil DeFranco building an empire|publisher=San Francisco Gate|work=The Technology Chronicles|date=February 6, 2012|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/philip-defranco-hit-youtube-sourcefed/|title=Philip DeFranco's latest YouTube venture is a hit|work=Daily Dot|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=E\u00f6rd\u00f6gh|first=Fruzsina|url=http://readwrite.com/2012/08/02/youtube-premium-channel-sourcefed-racks-up-50-000-subscribers#awesm=~ob6nsElJ0rYePB|title=YouTube Premium Channel SourceFed Racks Up 500,000 Subscribers|publisher=Readwrite|date=August 2, 2012|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> DeFranco, along with ''SourceFed'' co-hosts [[Elliott Morgan]] and [[Meg Turney]], joined journalists at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] and the [[2012 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] as part of [[YouTube]]'s \"Elections Hub\".<ref name=LATimes1/><ref>{{cite news|last=Perigard|first=Mark|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/general/view/20220824social_politics_youtube_launches_hub_dedicated_to_round-the_clock_campaign_coverage/|title=YouTube launches 'hub' dedicated to 'round-the clock campaign coverage|newspaper=Boston Herald|date=August 24, 2012|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Meredith|first=Leslie|url=http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2012/08/23/youtube-launches-2012-elections-hub/|title=YouTube launches 2012 elections hub|publisher=Fox News|date=August 23, 2012|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> ''The Philip DeFranco Show'' and ''SourceFed'' were nominated for awards in the [[3rd Streamy Awards|3rd installment]] of the [[Streamy Awards]].<ref name=3rdstreamys>{{cite web|url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/3rd-annual-nominees/|title=3RD ANNUAL NOMINEES|publisher=Streamys|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Influence ===\nDue to joining YouTube in 2006 and soon gaining a sizable audience on the website, DeFranco has been described by Lucas Shaw of ''[[TheWrap]]'' as \"one of the first video bloggers to find success on YouTube, and has since built\", as well as having an, \"entrepreneurial spirit and understanding of YouTube\".<ref name=Shaw13>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|url=http://www.thewrap.com/exclusive-phil-defranco-launch-first-new-channel-discovery/|title=YouTube Pioneer Phil DeFranco to Launch First New Channel for Discovery (Exclusive)|website=TheWrap|date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> David Cornell of ''The Inquisitr News'' writes that DeFranco is \"one of the leading sources of news\" on YouTube, later adding, \"Philip DeFranco is a YouTube success story.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Cornell|first=David|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/910104/youtube-proposal-philip-defranco-pops-the-question-video/#6qhcXw3uBSgkmXjc.99|title=YouTube Proposal: Philip DeFranco Pops The Question [Video]|work=The Inquisitr News|date=August 18, 2013|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> Alex Iansiti of ''[[Huffington Post]]'' noted, \"''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]'' is a great example of a media company to sprout out of YouTube\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Iansiti|first=Alex|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alex-iansiti/the-internet-ate-my-newsp_b_6773380.html|title=The Internet Ate My Newspaper|work=Huffington Post|date=February 28, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' has described DeFranco as, \"the [[Walter Cronkite]] for the YouTube generation who generates hundreds of headlines in under 10 minutes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-fi-philip-defranco-show-youtube-pictures-photogallery.html|title=Behind the scenes at YouTube's \"The Philip DeFranco Show\"|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> Sarah Kessler of ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' has referred to DeFranco as his generation's \"[[Jon Stewart]], if not [[Rupert Murdoch]] and [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kessler|first=Sarah|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3033554/inside-youtubes-fame-factory|title=Inside YouTube's Fame Factory|magazine=Fast Company|date=August 4, 2014|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===BetterHelp controversy===\nIn October 2018, [[BetterHelp]] gained attention from [[YouTube]] personalities after concerns were raised about alleged use of [[Unfair business practices|unfair pricing]], paid reviews from actors, and questionable terms of service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.betterhelp.com/terms/|title=Terms and Conditions|date=October 4, 2018|website=BetterHelp|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Along with creators like [[Shane Dawson]], DeFranco faced backlash for being among their most high-profile supporters. Both DeFranco and BetterHelp CEO Alon Matas addressed the issue, giving statements to [[Polygon (website)|''Polygon'']]'s Julia Alexander.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/15/17967362/philip-defranco-betterhelp-scam-drama-youtube|title=Philip DeFranco, BetterHelp CEO speak out on YouTube's mental health controversy|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=Oct 15, 2018|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> On October 15, DeFranco tweeted that he had formally ended his relationship with BetterHelp.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1051954343513976833|user=PhillyD|title=Before posting today's show I wanted to release a final update regarding BetterHelp. Thank you for taking the time to read.|author=Philip DeFranco|date=October 15, 2018|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political and religious views==\n\nPolitically, he is a [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]]<ref name=DailyPaul>{{cite web|last=Wampfler|first=Josiah|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004042800/http://www.dailypaul.com/256966/philip-defranco-comes-out-in-support-of-gary-johnson|url=http://www.dailypaul.com/256966/philip-defranco-comes-out-in-support-of-gary-johnson|title=Philip DeFranco Comes out In Support of Gary Johnson|publisher=Daily Paul|date=October 1, 2012|archive-date=October 4, 2012}}</ref> and voted for Libertarian nominee [[Gary Johnson]] in the [[2012 United States presidential election]].<ref name=DailyPaul/> DeFranco has described his political views as, \"fiscally conservative, socially liberal, for the most part.\"<ref>{{cite AV media|last=DeFranco|first=Philip|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ehdrOyY6Yqw|title=Giving Back vs. Keeping Mine|publisher=YouTube|work=The Vloggity|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=January 22, 2015}}</ref> DeFranco has used [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] in the past, stating, \"I have a prescription and I take it to sleep. Also if it makes the movie I'm falling asleep to 10x funnier, that is a side effect I am ok with.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/zsbq3/iama_philip_defranco_type_person_ama/c67abcm|title=IAMA Philip DeFranco Type Person AMA|publisher=Reddit|date=September 21, 2012|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeFranco was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], but later became an [[Atheism|atheist]].<ref name=atheistdec2013>{{cite AV media|last=DeFranco|first=Philip|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=phjRySZU3io|title=IDIOT ROBBER SHOT. THEN IT GETS EVEN FUNNIER.|publisher=YouTube|work=[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDeFranco has [[polycystic kidney disease]] which he inherited from his father and grandfather.<ref name=\"Philip DeFranco is sxephil\" />\n\nAs of 2020, DeFranco lives in [[Encino, Los Angeles]] with his wife, travel vlogger Lindsay Jordan DeFranco (n\u00e9e Doty) and their two sons. DeFranco proposed to Lindsay, then his longtime girlfriend, on August 16, 2013 at his \"DeFranco Loves Dat AZ\" show in [[Tempe, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/08/19/philip-defranco-linz-loves-proposal/|title=Philip DeFranco Proposed To His Girlfriend In Front Of 600 Fans|publisher=Tubefilter|date=August 19, 2013|accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/20/philip-defranco_n_3786096.html|title=Philip DeFranco, YouTube Personality, Proposes To Girlfriend During 'DeFranco Does Arizona' Show (VIDEO)|work=Huffington Post|date=August 20, 2013|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> Their first son, named Philip James \"Trey\" DeFranco III, was born in 2014.<ref name=babydefranco>{{cite web|last=DeFranco|first=Philip|url=https://twitter.com/PhillyD/status/458704481203400708|title=Welcome to the world 8 lbs 11 oz #BabyDeFranco|publisher=Twitter|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The couple married on March 7, 2015, and it was captured on social media.<ref name=Votta15>{{cite news|last=Votta|first=Rae|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/phil-defranco-lindsay-doty-wedding/|title=YouTube royalty Phil DeFranco and Lindsay Doty tie the knot|work=The Daily Dot|date=March 10, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Klima|first=Jeff|url=http://newmediarockstars.com/2015/03/philip-defranco-wedding-video-is-on-youtube/|title=Philip DeFranco Wedding Video Is On YouTube|magazine=New Media Rockstars|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> Their second son, Carter William DeFranco, was born in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/LinzDeFranco/status/906102545587642368|title=Tweet from Lindsay DeFranco|website=Twitter|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Work\n! Category\n! Award\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2008\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Philip DeFranco\n| Sexiest Geek\n| ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' magazine\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=Wallace08/>\n|-\n| 2010\n| God of the Year\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[2nd Streamy Awards]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/2010-nominees/|title=2nd Annual Nominees & Winners|publisher=Streamys|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"|2013\n| rowspan=\"4\"|''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n| Best News Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[International Academy of Web Television#IAWTV Awards|2nd IAWTV Awards]]\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iawtv.org/news/2013/7/19/2013-iawtv-awards-winners|title= 2013 IAWTV Awards Winners|publisher=International Academy of Web Television|date=January 9, 2013|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Writing (Non-Fiction)\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://newmediarockstars.com/2012/11/break-out-the-award-polish-and-kleenex-the-iawtv-award-nominees-are-in/|title=Break Out The Award Polish And Kleenex: The IAWTV Award Nominees Are In|magazine=New Media Rockstars|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best First-Person Series\n| rowspan=\"6\"|[[3rd Streamy Awards]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Best News and Culture Series\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[SourceFed]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| Audience Choice for Best Series of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| Best Live Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| [[SourceFed#2012 Election Hub|''SourceFed: #PDSLive 2012 Election Night Coverage]]\n| Best Live Event\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=3rdstreamys/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2014\n| ''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n| Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| rowspan=\"4\"|[[4th_Streamy_Awards|4th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=4thstreamys>{{cite web|url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/4th-annual-nominees-winners/|title=4th Annual Streamy Awards Nominees|publisher=Streamys|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[SourceFed]]''\n| News and Current Events\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=4thstreamys/>\n|-\n| Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=4thstreamys/>\n|-\n| ''SourceFed Nerd''\n| Gaming\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=4thstreamys/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Streamy Awards|5th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"5thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/5th-annual-nominees-winners/|title=5th Annual Winners & Nominees|language=en-US|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"5thstreamys\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[6th_Streamy_Awards|6th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/10/streamy-awards-2016-winners-announced-1201829667/|title=2016 Streamy Awards: Full Winners List|last=Lincoln|first=Ross A.|date=October 2, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[7th_Streamy_Awards|7th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"7thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/2017/09/winners-announced-for-the-7th-annual-streamy-awards/|title=2016 Winners Announced for the 7th Annual Streamy Awards|last=Brown|first=Kelsey|date=September 26, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"7thstreamys2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/7th-annual-nominees/|title=7th Annual Nominees|language=en-US|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|Best News and Culture Series\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[8th_Streamy_Awards|8th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref name=\"8thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/8th-annual-nominees/|title=8th Annual Nominees & Winners|language=en-US|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|Audience Choice for Best Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"8thstreamys\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[The Philip DeFranco Show]]''\n|News\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[9th_Streamy_Awards|9th Streamy Awards]]\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref name=\"9thstreamys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.streamys.org/2019/12/winners-announced-for-the-9th-annual-streamy-awards/|title=Winners Announced for the 9th Annual Streamy Awards|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Show of the Year\n| {{Nominated}}\n|<ref name=\"9thstreamys\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Viral marketing]]\n* ''[[BlackBoxTV Presents]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Defranco, Philip}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century atheists]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the online media industry]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American media company founders]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:East Carolina University alumni]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Maker Studios people]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:SourceFed people]]\n[[Category:Streamy Award winners]]\n[[Category:University of South Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:Video bloggers]]\n[[Category:Video game commentators]]\n[[Category:Male bloggers]]\n", "name_user": "Soulbust", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_DeFranco"}
{"title_page": "Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox road\n|country=USA\n|header_type=historic\n|marker_image=none\n|allocation={{plainlist|1=\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|191}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|40}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|64}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|139}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|I|70|US|6|US|50}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|I|70|US|6|US|50}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|UT|128}}\n}}\n|name=Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway\n|map=DinosaurDiamond map.svg\n|length_mi=512\n|length_round=0\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"DD\"/>\n|established=2002\n|decommissioned=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Price, Utah]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b= [[Grand Junction, Colorado]]\n|junction=\n|states=[[Utah]], [[Colorado]]\n|counties='''Utah''': [[Carbon County, Utah|Carbon]], [[Duchesne County, Utah|Duchesne]], [[Grand County, Utah|Grand]], [[Emery County, Utah|Emery]]<br>'''Colorado''': [[Moffat County, Colorado|Moffat]], [[Rio Blanco County, Colorado|Rio Blanco]], [[Garfield County, Colorado|Garfield]], [[Mesa County, Colorado|Mesa]]\n|system='''[[National Scenic Byway]]s'''<br />{{Infobox road/browselinks/USA|state=UT}}{{Infobox road/browselinks/USA|state=CO}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway''' (also '''Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway''') is a {{convert|512|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}}<ref name=\"DD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dinosaurdiamond.org/About.htm |title=About the Scenic Byway |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Dinosaurdiamond.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221203503/http://www.dinosaurdiamond.org/About.htm |archivedate=February 21, 2008 }}</ref> [[National Scenic Byway]] in the U.S. states of [[Utah]] and [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradobyways.org/ByWay.cfm?byWayIDpar=DIN20011203092317 |title=Dinosaur Diamond |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Coloradobyways.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917133050/http://www.coloradobyways.org/Byway.cfm?byWayIDpar=DIN20011203092317 |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> The highway forms a diamond-shaped loop with [[Vertex (geometry)|vertices]] at [[Moab, Utah|Moab]], [[Helper, Utah|Helper]], [[Vernal, Utah|Vernal]] and [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]].\n\nThe segment within [[Utah]] is known as the '''Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway'''. The segment within [[Colorado]] is known as the '''Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway'''. Notable features surrounding the Dinosaur Diamond include [[Dinosaur National Monument]], the [[Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area]], [[Canyonlands National Park]], [[Arches National Park]], [[Natural Bridges National Monument]], [[Colorado National Monument]], and several national forests.\n\nThe path of [[Interstate 70 in Colorado|Interstate 70]] (I&#8209;70) in Colorado is derived from two previous highways, [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|U.S. Highway 6]] (US&nbsp;6) and [[U.S. Route 40 in Colorado|US&nbsp;40]]. US&nbsp;40 was an original piece of the [[U.S. Highway]] system commissioned in 1926. The portion now numbered [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] came about in 1937 when the route over [[Vail Pass]] was paved. The first route through the path of I-70 in Utah was the [[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Old Spanish Trail]], a trade route between [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]], and [[Los Angeles, California]]. The trail was in common use before the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in 1848.\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Colorado===\nThe following Colorado routes are included in the Colorado portion of the Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway:<ref name=\"DD\" />\n* {{Jct|state=CO|I|70}} between [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] and the Utah state line. (I-70 runs [[concurrency (road)|concurrently]] with [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 50 in Colorado|US&nbsp;50]] in this area)\n* {{Jct|state=CO|US|40}} between [[Dinosaur, Colorado|Dinosaur]] and the Utah state line\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|64}} between Dinosaur and [[Rangely, Colorado|Rangely]]\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|139}} between [[Fruita, Colorado|Fruita]] and Rangely\n\nThe easternmost starting point of the Dinosaur Diamond (DD) begins in Grand Junction, Colorado, on I-70.<ref name=\"DD\" /> In the vicinity of Grand Junction are the [[White River National Forest|White River]], [[Uncompahgre National Forest|Uncompahgre]], and [[Grand Mesa National Forest]]s.<ref name=google>{{google maps |title=Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=N+Hwy-191%2FUS&nbsp;191&daddr=UT-128+to:UT-128+to:UT-128+to:Unknown+road+to:E+Main+St%2FUS&nbsp;40+to:N+Hwy-6%2FUS&nbsp;191%2FUS&nbsp;6+to:38.601579,-109.575663&geocode=FSEDTQIdGgJ4-Q%3BFfg-TgId_0J6-Q%3BFdUMUgIdo4p7-Q%3BFTq-UgIdFC98-Q%3BFRDLVAIdEM6H-Q%3BFRROaQIdd7p4-Q%3BFQClXQIdJnJk-Q%3B&hl=en&mra=dme&mrcr=3&mrsp=7&sz=14&via=1,2,3&sll=38.608018,-109.577723&sspn=0.031456,0.054932&ie=UTF8&ll=39.58029,-109.418335&spn=1.985541,3.515625&z=8 |accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref> Other notable features nearby include the [[Powderhorn Resort]], and the geologic features of [[Book Cliffs]] and [[Grand Mesa]].\n[[File:Dinosaur National Monument-inside the Dinosaur Quarry building.jpeg|thumb|left|Workers extracting dinosaur bones at [[Dinosaur National Monument]]]]\n\nTraveling about {{convert|10|mi|km}} westbound on I-70 will lead to Fruita, a small town within view of the [[Colorado National Monument]],<ref name=google/> which features numerous scenic hiking trails. From the trails, one may view attractions such as the Book Cliffs and Coke Ovens overlooks, and unique rock formations such as Independence Monument and the \"Kissing Couple\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/colm/planyourvisit/hiking.htm|title=Colorado National Monument: Hiking|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref>  Fruita is also the home of [[Mike the Headless Chicken]], and hosts an annual festival in his honor every May. A small statue dedicated to Mike can also be seen in the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/attract/COFRUchicken.html |title=Mike, the Headless Chicken Fruita, Colorado |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Roadsideamerica.com}}</ref>\n\nJust west of Fruita, the byway turns north onto SH-139, traveling {{convert|78|mi|km}} to the next town of Rangely, and traversing the [[Douglas Pass]].<ref name=google/> Nearby attractions include the Rangely Outdoor Museum and the [[Ca\u00f1on Pintado]] (\"painted canyon\") Historic District [[petroglyph]]s, which is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangely.com/CanyonPintado.htm|title=Canyon Pintado: Rangely|publisher=Rangely.com|accessdate=May 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912232037/http://www.rangely.com/CanyonPintado.htm|archive-date=September 12, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangelychamber.com/aboutus.htm |title=About Us |publisher=Rangely Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725064523/http://www.rangelychamber.com/aboutus.htm |archivedate=July 25, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe byway continues {{convert|18|mi|km}} northwest on SH-64, to the small town of Dinosaur.<ref name=google/> Nearby Dinosaur is the \"crown jewel\" of the DD, the [[Dinosaur National Monument]], which claims to be the most productive [[Jurassic Period]] dinosaur quarry in the world. The monument includes a walkway where visitors can view a [[sandstone]] wall embedded with over 2,000 dinosaur bones, and watch [[paleontologists]] chip away the sandstone to expose the fossilized dinosaur bones. Visitors can also see the preparation laboratory where dinosaur [[fossil]]s are cleaned and preserved.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utah.com/nationalsites/dinosaur.htm |title=Dinosaur National Monument |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Utah.com }}</ref>\n\nUpon leaving Dinosaur, the DD continues west on US&nbsp;40 and crosses the border into Utah.<ref name=google/>\n\n===Utah===\nThe Utah portion of the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway is routed along these highways:<ref name=\"DD\"/>\n* {{Jct|state=UT|I|70}} between Colorado state line and [[Cisco, Utah|Cisco]], again from [[Crescent Junction, Utah|Crescent Junction]] to [[Green River, Utah|Green River]] (I-70 runs concurrently with [[U.S. Route 6 in Utah|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 50 in Utah|US&nbsp;50]] in this area)\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|6}} from Green River to [[Helper, Utah|Helper]]\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|40}} from [[Vernal, Utah|Vernal]] to Colorado state line\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|191}} from [[Moab, Utah|Moab]] to Vernal\n* {{Jct|state=UT|UT|128}} from Cisco to Moab\n[[File:UTSR128.JPG|thumb|right|[[Utah State Route 128|SR-128]], one of the highways forming the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Byway]]\n[[File:Archaic & Fremont Indian petroglyphs (~6000 B.C. to ~1300 A.D.) (Potash Petroglyphs, along the Colorado River, eastern Utah, USA) 9 (22851794891).jpg|thumb|Potash Road Petroglyphs, on [[Utah State Route 279]] near Moab]]\nTraveling {{convert|34|mi|km}} west of Dinosaur, Colorado, the Dinosaur Diamond encounters the small city of Vernal, Utah. Vernal borders the western end of the Dinosaur National Monument; other notable attractions nearby include [[Steinaker State Park]], [[Red Fleet State Park]], [[Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area]], and the [[Ashley National Forest]].<ref name=google/>\n\nContinuing along the Dinosaur Diamond, US&nbsp;40 and US&nbsp;191 converge within Vernal, heading west for {{convert|30|mi|km}} to the city of [[Roosevelt, Utah|Roosevelt]]. Roosevelt is located on the edge of the [[Uintah and Ouray Indian Reservation]]. Heading {{convert|29|mi}} to the west is the [[county seat]] of [[Duchesne, Utah|Duchesne]], located within the reservation. Nearby Duchesne are [[Starvation State Park]]<ref name=google/> and [[Kings Peak (Utah)|Kings Peak]] (the highest point in Utah), which is part of the Uinta Mountain range. The [[Uinta Mountains]] are one of the few mountain ranges in the [[contiguous United States]] which run east\u2013west, and are the highest range to do so.<ref>{{cite peakbagger |pid=5507 |name=Kings Peak, Utah |accessdate=February 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWithin Duchesne, US&nbsp;40 and US&nbsp;191 diverge, and the DD continues {{convert|55|mi|km}} south along US&nbsp;191 over an unnamed [[mountain pass]], through the small town of Helper, and into the larger city of [[Price, Utah|Price]]. The numerous attractions surrounding Price include [[College of Eastern Utah Prehistoric Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceumuseum.freewebsitehosting.com/information.htm |title=Information |publisher=College of Eastern Utah Prehistoric Museum |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222221344/http://www.ceumuseum.freewebsitehosting.com/information.htm |archivedate=February 22, 2010 }}</ref> [[Manti-La Sal National Forest]], [[Huntington Lake State Park]], [[Scofield State Park]],<ref name=google/> and [[Ninemile Canyon (Utah)|Ninemile Canyon]] which features numerous petroglyphs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninemilecanyoncoalition.org/|title=Nine Mile Canyon Coalition|publisher=Nine Mile Canyon Coalition|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref> Also nearby is the [[Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry]], a prehistoric mud trap which claims to be the densest concentration of Jurassic dinosaur fossils in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castlecountry.com/what_to_see/san_rafael_swell/dinosaur_quarry.html |title=Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Utah's Castle Country }}</ref>\n\nTraveling {{convert|63|mi|km}} southeast along US&nbsp;191, the DD encounters the city of Green River.<ref name=google/> Notable features surrounding Green River include the [[San Rafael Swell]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanrafaelswell.org/whereis/whereis.php |title=Where is the Swell? |publisher=Sanrafaelswell.org |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427133449/http://www.sanrafaelswell.org/whereis/whereis.php |archivedate=April 27, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> [[Green River State Park]], and [[Goblin Valley State Park]].<ref name=google/> Also nearby is [[Crystal Geyser]], a rare (but man-made) cold water geyser caused by the expansion of carbonized \"soda pop\" water within.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uweb.ucsb.edu/~glennon/crystalgeyser/|title=Carbon-Dioxide-Driven, Cold-Water Geysers|publisher=[[University of California Santa Barbara]]|accessdate=May 9, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423220827/http://www.uweb.ucsb.edu/~glennon/crystalgeyser/|archivedate=April 23, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within Green River, US&nbsp;191 converges with I-70 for a short while and diverges again, south towards the city of Moab, {{convert|55|mi|km}} from Green River.\n\nJust south of the junction of US&nbsp;191 and SR-128, the city of Moab features a number of nearby attractions. [[Arches National Park]], [[Canyonlands National Park]], [[Dead Horse Point State Park]],<ref name=google/> and the [[Newspaper Rock State Historic Monument|Newspaper Rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utah.com/schmerker/2000/newsrock.htm|title=Articles: Newspaper Rock|publisher=Utah Travel Industry Website|accessdate=May 9, 2009|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66j4Z6157?url=http://www.utah.com/schmerker/2000/newsrock.htm|archive-date=April 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Utah State Route 279|Potash Road]] petroglyphs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discovermoab.com/byways.htm|title=Moab Scenic Auto Tours|publisher=Moab Area Travel Council|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLeaving Moab, the DD continues north along SR-128 to its terminus with I-70 in Cisco. Traveling east along I-70, before completing the \"diamond\" back in Grand Junction, Colorado.<ref name=google />\n\n==History==\nThe segment within Colorado was designated the Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway by the Colorado Transportation Commission in 1997. The segment within Utah was designated the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway by the [[Utah State Legislature]] in 1998. The highway was approved as a [[National Scenic Byway]] in 2002.<ref name=\"DD\" />\n\nNational Scenic Byways must go through a nomination procedure, and must already be designated as a state [[scenic byway]] in order to be nominated (However, roads that meet all criteria and requirements for national designation but not state or designation criteria may be considered for national designation on a case-by-case basis).<ref name=policy>{{cite web|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=1995_register&docid=fr18my95-105|title=National Scenic Byways Program Interim Policy|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|accessdate=May 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nTo be considered for designation \"a road or highway must significantly meet at least one of the six scenic byways intrinsic qualities\". The qualities are scenic, natural, historic, cultural, archeological, or recreational. A \"corridor management plan\" must also be developed, with community involvement, and the plan \"should provide for the conservation and enhancement of the byway's intrinsic qualities as well as the promotion of tourism and economic development\". The final step is when the highway (or highways) is approved for designation by the [[Secretary of Transportation]].<ref name=policy />\n\n===Colorado history===\nThe path of I-70 in Colorado is derived from two previous highways, [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 40 in Colorado|US&nbsp;40]]. US&nbsp;40 was an original piece of the [[U.S. Highway]] system commissioned in 1926. The portion now numbered US&nbsp;6 came about in 1937 when the route over [[Vail Pass]] was paved. A portion of this route was also numbered [[U.S. Route 24 in Colorado|US&nbsp;24]] at the time.<ref name=broer>{{cite map |publisher=Rand McNally |title=Road Atlas |via=Broer Map Library) |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/Southwest/randmcnally_ra_1946_022.html |year=1946 |page=24 |accessdate=May 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1920s, SH-139 was an unimproved road from US&nbsp;6 at Fruita north to SH-64 in Rangely.<ref>{{cite map |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/NorthernRockies/Colorado/unitedstates1926ra_062.html |publisher=Rand McNally |title=Junior Road Map: Colorado |accessdate=April 25, 2009 |year=1926 |via=Broer Map Library}}</ref>\n\n===Utah history===\n[[Image:HuntSceneNMC.JPG|thumb|right|[[Petroglyph]]s inside [[Ninemile Canyon (Utah)|Ninemile Canyon]]]]\n\nThe first route through this portion of Utah was the [[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Old Spanish Trail]], a trade route between [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]] and [[Los Angeles, California]]. The trail was in common use before the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in 1848.<ref name=oldspanishtrail>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/trail_history.php |title=Old Spanish Trail History |accessdate=March 19, 2008 |last=von Till Warren |first=Elizabeth |publisher=Old Spanish Trail Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308045310/http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/trail_history.php |archivedate=March 8, 2008 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although the trail serves a different route than I-70, they were both intended to connect southern California with points further east. I-70 generally parallels the route of the Old Spanish Trail west of [[Crescent Junction, Utah|Crescent Junction]].<ref name=oldspanishtrail2>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/maps.php |title=Old Spanish Trail Association: Maps |accessdate=February 28, 2008 |publisher=Old Spanish Trail Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080201122612/http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/maps.php |archivedate=February 1, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Utah State Road Commission]] took over US&nbsp;40 from Kimball Junction to Colorado in 1910 and 1911,<ref name=history-6>{{cite web |publisher=[[Utah Department of Transportation]] |url=http://www.udot.utah.gov/download.php/tid=1348/SR-006.pdf |format=PDF |title=Route 6 history |date=September 2005 |access-date=April 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005120302/http://www2.udot.utah.gov/download.php/tid=1348/SR-006.pdf |archive-date=October 5, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and assigned the SR-6 designation to this route by the mid-1920s.<ref name=\"1926 Rand McNally\">{{cite map |publisher=[[Rand McNally]] |title=Auto Road Atlas |year=1926 |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/ |via=Broer Map Library}}</ref> In late 1926, the [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] (AASHO) assigned the designation of US&nbsp;40 to this cross-state route, consisting of most of SR-4 and all of SR-6.<ref name=\"1926 map\">{{cite map |publisher=[[Bureau of Public Roads]] |title=United States System of Highways Adopted for Uniform Marking by the American Association of State Highway Officials |url=http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth298433/m1/1/zoom/ |date=November 11, 1926 |accessdate=November 7, 2013 |scale=1:7,000,000 |cartography=U.S. Geological Survey |oclc=32889555}}</ref> (The SR-6 designation remained until the [[1977 renumbering (Utah)|1977 renumbering]]; SR-4 became [[Utah State Route 2 (1962-1977)|SR-2]] in 1962 and was eliminated in favor of [[I-80 (UT)|I-80]] in 1977.)\n\nThe road connecting [[Colton, Utah|Colton]] on [[Utah State Route 8 (1920s-1977)|SR-8]] (US&nbsp;50, now US&nbsp;6) with [[Utah State Route 6 (1920s-1977)|SR-6]] (US&nbsp;40) in [[Duchesne, Utah|Duchesne]] became a state highway in 1910. The southwest end was moved from Colton to [[Castle Gate, Utah|Castle Gate]] in 1912<!--include more history of the Emma Park Road here?-->,<ref name=resolutions-33>{{cite web |publisher=[[Utah Department of Transportation]] |work= Highway Resolutions |url=http://www.udot.utah.gov/main/uconowner.gf?n=200609140937301 |title=Route 33 |format=PDF |date=October 2007 |accessdate=May 2008}}</ref> and in 1927 it was numbered State Route 33.<ref>{{cite UTSR law|year=1927|quote=33. From Castle Gate northeasterly to Duchesne.}}</ref> Few changes were made to the roadway, and in 1981 it became part of US&nbsp;191.<ref name=resolutions-33 />\n\nAccess between Moab and Castle Valley was originally via a [[pack trail]] called the Heavenly Stairway. This trail, named for a dramatic descent of over {{convert|1000|ft|m}}, was described as beautiful, but difficult to navigate.<ref name=\"grandmemories\">{{cite book |last=Daughters of Utah Pioneers |authorlink=Daughters of Utah Pioneers |title=Grand Memories |year=1972 |pages=127, 144 |oclc=4790603}}</ref> Isolated from Utah's population centers, this area depended on [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] and other cities in Colorado for both everyday supplies and a market for agricultural products.<ref name=\"utahdotgov\">{{cite web |url=http://history.utah.gov/apps/markers/detailed_results.php?markerid=2944 |title=Utah History Resource Center: Markers and Monuments, Dewey Bridge |date=October 2006 |accessdate=October 13, 2007 |publisher=State of Utah |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121214152409/http://history.utah.gov/apps/markers/detailed_results.php?markerid=2944 |archivedate=December 14, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Moab residents pushed for a road to be built along the riverbank. By 1902, the trail was replaced with a toll road, called King's Toll Road, after Samuel King. King was an early settler who also operated the toll [[ferry]] used prior to the construction of the [[Dewey Bridge]]. Rocks inscribed with \"Kings Toll Road\" can still be found along the roadway. While the road did improve travel, it was not built high enough above the river level and was often flooded.<ref name=\"grandmemories\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|U.S. Roads|Colorado|Utah}}\n* [[Grand Mesa Scenic and Historic Byway]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway}}\n* [http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/byways/2474 Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway], Federal Highway Administration\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111113154915/http://dinosaurdiamond.org/ Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway at dinosaurdiamond.org] - via the Wayback Machine\n* [http://www.utah.com/byways/dinosaur_diamond.htm Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway], Utah Office of Tourism\n\n[[Category:National Scenic Byways in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Utah Scenic Byways]]\n[[Category:Colorado Scenic Byways]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Carbon County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Duchesne County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Grand County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Emery County, Utah|Transportation in Emery County]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Moffat County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Rio Blanco County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Garfield County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Mesa County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Carbon County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Duchesne County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Grand County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Emery County, Utah|Visitor attractions in Emery County]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Moffat County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Rio Blanco County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Garfield County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Mesa County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Interstate 70]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 6]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 40]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 50]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox road\n|country=USA\n|header_type=historic\n|marker_image=none\n|allocation={{plainlist|1=\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|191}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|40}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|64}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|139}}\n* {{Jct|state=CO|I|70|US|6|US|50}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|I|70|US|6|US|50}}\n* {{Jct|state=UT|UT|128}}\n}}\n|name=Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway\n|map=DinosaurDiamond map.svg\n|length_mi=512\n|length_round=0\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"DD\"/>\n|established=2002\n|decommissioned=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Price, Utah]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b= [[Grand Junction, Colorado]]\n|junction=\n|states=[[Utah]], [[Colorado]]\n|counties='''Utah''': [[Carbon County, Utah|Carbon]], [[Duchesne County, Utah|Duchesne]], [[Grand County, Utah|Grand]], [[Emery County, Utah|Emery]]<br>'''Colorado''': [[Moffat County, Colorado|Moffat]], [[Rio Blanco County, Colorado|Rio Blanco]], [[Garfield County, Colorado|Garfield]], [[Mesa County, Colorado|Mesa]]\n|system='''[[National Scenic Byway]]s'''<br />{{Infobox road/browselinks/USA|state=UT}}{{Infobox road/browselinks/USA|state=CO}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway''' (also '''Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway''') is a {{convert|512|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}}<ref name=\"DD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dinosaurdiamond.org/About.htm |title=About the Scenic Byway |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Dinosaurdiamond.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221203503/http://www.dinosaurdiamond.org/About.htm |archivedate=February 21, 2008 }}</ref> [[National Scenic Byway]] in the U.S. states of [[Utah]] and [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradobyways.org/ByWay.cfm?byWayIDpar=DIN20011203092317 |title=Dinosaur Diamond |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Coloradobyways.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917133050/http://www.coloradobyways.org/Byway.cfm?byWayIDpar=DIN20011203092317 |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> The highway forms a diamond-shaped loop with [[Vertex (geometry)|vertices]] at [[Moab, Utah|Moab]], [[Helper, Utah|Helper]], [[Vernal, Utah|Vernal]] and [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]].\n\nThe segment within [[Utah]] is known as the '''Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway'''. The segment within [[Colorado]] is known as the '''Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway'''. Notable features surrounding the Dinosaur Diamond include [[Dinosaur National Monument]], the [[Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area]], [[Canyonlands National Park]], [[Arches National Park]], [[Natural Bridges National Monument]], [[Colorado National Monument]], and several national forests.\n\nThe path of [[Interstate 70 in Colorado|Interstate 70]] (I&#8209;70) in Colorado is derived from two previous highways, [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|U.S. Highway 6]] (US&nbsp;6) and [[U.S. Route 40 in Colorado|US&nbsp;40]]. US&nbsp;40 was an original piece of the [[U.S. Highway]] system commissioned in 1926. The portion now numbered [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] came about in 1937 when the route over [[Vail Pass]] was paved. The first route through the path of I-70 in Utah was the [[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Old Spanish Trail]], a trade route between [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]], and [[Los Angeles, California]]. The trail was in common use before the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in 1848.\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Colorado===\nThe following Colorado routes are included in the Colorado portion of the Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway:<ref name=\"DD\" />\n* {{Jct|state=CO|I|70}} between [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] and the Utah state line. (I-70 runs [[concurrency (road)|concurrently]] with [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 50 in Colorado|US&nbsp;50]] in this area)\n* {{Jct|state=CO|US|40}} between [[Dinosaur, Colorado|Dinosaur]] and the Utah state line\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|64}} between Dinosaur and [[Rangely, Colorado|Rangely]]\n* {{Jct|state=CO|CO|139}} between [[Fruita, Colorado|Fruita]] and Rangely\n\nThe easternmost starting point of the Dinosaur Diamond (DD) begins in Grand Junction, Colorado, on I-70.<ref name=\"DD\" /> In the vicinity of Grand Junction are the [[White River National Forest|White River]], [[Uncompahgre National Forest|Uncompahgre]], and [[Grand Mesa National Forest]]s.<ref name=google>{{google maps |title=Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=N+Hwy-191%2FUS&nbsp;191&daddr=UT-128+to:UT-128+to:UT-128+to:Unknown+road+to:E+Main+St%2FUS&nbsp;40+to:N+Hwy-6%2FUS&nbsp;191%2FUS&nbsp;6+to:38.601579,-109.575663&geocode=FSEDTQIdGgJ4-Q%3BFfg-TgId_0J6-Q%3BFdUMUgIdo4p7-Q%3BFTq-UgIdFC98-Q%3BFRDLVAIdEM6H-Q%3BFRROaQIdd7p4-Q%3BFQClXQIdJnJk-Q%3B&hl=en&mra=dme&mrcr=3&mrsp=7&sz=14&via=1,2,3&sll=38.608018,-109.577723&sspn=0.031456,0.054932&ie=UTF8&ll=39.58029,-109.418335&spn=1.985541,3.515625&z=8 |accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref> Other notable features nearby include the [[Powderhorn Resort]], and the geologic features of [[Book Cliffs]] and [[Grand Mesa]].\n[[File:Dinosaur National Monument-inside the Dinosaur Quarry building.jpeg|thumb|left|Workers extracting dinosaur bones at [[Dinosaur National Monument]]]]\n\nTraveling about {{convert|10|mi|km}} westbound on I-70 will lead to Fruita, a small town within view of the [[Colorado National Monument]],<ref name=google/> which features numerous scenic hiking trails. From the trails, one may view attractions such as the Book Cliffs and Coke Ovens overlooks, and unique rock formations such as Independence Monument and the \"Kissing Couple\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/colm/planyourvisit/hiking.htm|title=Colorado National Monument: Hiking|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref>  Fruita is also the home of [[Mike the Headless Chicken]], and hosts an annual festival in his honor every May. A small statue dedicated to Mike can also be seen in the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/attract/COFRUchicken.html |title=Mike, the Headless Chicken Fruita, Colorado |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Roadsideamerica.com}}</ref>\n\nJust west of Fruita, the byway turns north onto SH-139, traveling {{convert|78|mi|km}} to the next town of Rangely, and traversing the [[Douglas Pass]].<ref name=google/> Nearby attractions include the Rangely Outdoor Museum and the [[Ca\u00f1on Pintado]] (\"painted canyon\") Historic District [[petroglyph]]s, which is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangely.com/CanyonPintado.htm|title=Canyon Pintado: Rangely|publisher=Rangely.com|accessdate=May 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912232037/http://www.rangely.com/CanyonPintado.htm|archive-date=September 12, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangelychamber.com/aboutus.htm |title=About Us |publisher=Rangely Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725064523/http://www.rangelychamber.com/aboutus.htm |archivedate=July 25, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe byway continues {{convert|18|mi|km}} northwest on SH-64, to the small town of Dinosaur.<ref name=google/> Nearby Dinosaur is the \"crown jewel\" of the DD, the [[Dinosaur National Monument]], which claims to be the most productive [[Jurassic Period]] dinosaur quarry in the world. The monument includes a walkway where visitors can view a [[sandstone]] wall embedded with over 2,000 dinosaur bones, and watch [[paleontologists]] chip away the sandstone to expose the fossilized dinosaur bones. Visitors can also see the preparation laboratory where dinosaur [[fossil]]s are cleaned and preserved.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utah.com/nationalsites/dinosaur.htm |title=Dinosaur National Monument |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Utah.com }}</ref>\n\nUpon leaving Dinosaur, the DD continues west on US&nbsp;40 and crosses the border into Utah.<ref name=google/>\n\n===Utah===\nThe Utah portion of the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway is routed along these highways:<ref name=\"DD\"/>\n* {{Jct|state=UT|I|70}} between Colorado state line and [[Cisco, Utah|Cisco]], again from [[Crescent Junction, Utah|Crescent Junction]] to [[Green River, Utah|Green River]] (I-70 runs concurrently with [[U.S. Route 6 in Utah|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 50 in Utah|US&nbsp;50]] in this area)\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|6}} from Green River to [[Helper, Utah|Helper]]\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|40}} from [[Vernal, Utah|Vernal]] to Colorado state line\n* {{Jct|state=UT|US|191}} from [[Moab, Utah|Moab]] to Vernal\n* {{Jct|state=UT|UT|128}} from Cisco to Moab\n[[File:UTSR128.JPG|thumb|right|[[Utah State Route 128|SR-128]], one of the highways forming the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Byway]]\n[[File:Archaic & Fremont Indian petroglyphs (~6000 B.C. to ~1300 A.D.) (Potash Petroglyphs, along the Colorado River, eastern Utah, USA) 9 (22851794891).jpg|thumb|Potash Road Petroglyphs, on [[Utah State Route 279]] near Moab]]\nTraveling {{convert|34|mi|km}} west of Dinosaur, Colorado, the Dinosaur Diamond encounters the small city of Vernal, Utah. Vernal borders the western end of the Dinosaur National Monument; other notable attractions nearby include [[Steinaker State Park]], [[Red Fleet State Park]], [[Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area]], and the [[Ashley National Forest]].<ref name=google/>\n\nContinuing along the Dinosaur Diamond, US&nbsp;40 and US&nbsp;191 converge within Vernal, heading west for {{convert|30|mi|km}} to the city of [[Roosevelt, Utah|Roosevelt]]. Roosevelt is located on the edge of the [[Uintah and Ouray Indian Reservation]]. Heading {{convert|29|mi}} to the west is the [[county seat]] of [[Duchesne, Utah|Duchesne]], located within the reservation. Nearby Duchesne are [[Starvation State Park]]<ref name=google/> and [[Kings Peak (Utah)|Kings Peak]] (the highest point in Utah), which is part of the Uinta Mountain range. The [[Uinta Mountains]] are one of the few mountain ranges in the [[contiguous United States]] which run east\u2013west, and are the highest range to do so.<ref>{{cite peakbagger |pid=5507 |name=Kings Peak, Utah |accessdate=February 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWithin Duchesne, US&nbsp;40 and US&nbsp;191 diverge, and the DD continues {{convert|55|mi|km}} south along US&nbsp;191 over an unnamed [[mountain pass]], through the small town of Helper, and into the larger city of [[Price, Utah|Price]]. The numerous attractions surrounding Price include [[College of Eastern Utah Prehistoric Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceumuseum.freewebsitehosting.com/information.htm |title=Information |publisher=College of Eastern Utah Prehistoric Museum |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222221344/http://www.ceumuseum.freewebsitehosting.com/information.htm |archivedate=February 22, 2010 }}</ref> [[Manti-La Sal National Forest]], [[Huntington Lake State Park]], [[Scofield State Park]],<ref name=google/> and [[Nine Mile Canyon]] which features numerous petroglyphs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninemilecanyoncoalition.org/|title=Nine Mile Canyon Coalition|publisher=Nine Mile Canyon Coalition|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref> Also nearby is the [[Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry]], a prehistoric mud trap which claims to be the densest concentration of Jurassic dinosaur fossils in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castlecountry.com/what_to_see/san_rafael_swell/dinosaur_quarry.html |title=Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Utah's Castle Country }}</ref>\n\nTraveling {{convert|63|mi|km}} southeast along US&nbsp;191, the DD encounters the city of Green River.<ref name=google/> Notable features surrounding Green River include the [[San Rafael Swell]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanrafaelswell.org/whereis/whereis.php |title=Where is the Swell? |publisher=Sanrafaelswell.org |accessdate=May 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427133449/http://www.sanrafaelswell.org/whereis/whereis.php |archivedate=April 27, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> [[Green River State Park]], and [[Goblin Valley State Park]].<ref name=google/> Also nearby is [[Crystal Geyser]], a rare (but man-made) cold water geyser caused by the expansion of carbonized \"soda pop\" water within.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uweb.ucsb.edu/~glennon/crystalgeyser/|title=Carbon-Dioxide-Driven, Cold-Water Geysers|publisher=[[University of California Santa Barbara]]|accessdate=May 9, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423220827/http://www.uweb.ucsb.edu/~glennon/crystalgeyser/|archivedate=April 23, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within Green River, US&nbsp;191 converges with I-70 for a short while and diverges again, south towards the city of Moab, {{convert|55|mi|km}} from Green River.\n\nJust south of the junction of US&nbsp;191 and SR-128, the city of Moab features a number of nearby attractions. [[Arches National Park]], [[Canyonlands National Park]], [[Dead Horse Point State Park]],<ref name=google/> and the [[Newspaper Rock State Historic Monument|Newspaper Rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utah.com/schmerker/2000/newsrock.htm|title=Articles: Newspaper Rock|publisher=Utah Travel Industry Website|accessdate=May 9, 2009|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66j4Z6157?url=http://www.utah.com/schmerker/2000/newsrock.htm|archive-date=April 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Utah State Route 279|Potash Road]] petroglyphs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discovermoab.com/byways.htm|title=Moab Scenic Auto Tours|publisher=Moab Area Travel Council|accessdate=May 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLeaving Moab, the DD continues north along SR-128 to its terminus with I-70 in Cisco. Traveling east along I-70, before completing the \"diamond\" back in Grand Junction, Colorado.<ref name=google />\n\n==History==\nThe segment within Colorado was designated the Dinosaur Diamond Scenic and Historic Byway by the Colorado Transportation Commission in 1997. The segment within Utah was designated the Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway by the [[Utah State Legislature]] in 1998. The highway was approved as a [[National Scenic Byway]] in 2002.<ref name=\"DD\" />\n\nNational Scenic Byways must go through a nomination procedure, and must already be designated as a state [[scenic byway]] in order to be nominated (However, roads that meet all criteria and requirements for national designation but not state or designation criteria may be considered for national designation on a case-by-case basis).<ref name=policy>{{cite web|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=1995_register&docid=fr18my95-105|title=National Scenic Byways Program Interim Policy|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|accessdate=May 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nTo be considered for designation \"a road or highway must significantly meet at least one of the six scenic byways intrinsic qualities\". The qualities are scenic, natural, historic, cultural, archeological, or recreational. A \"corridor management plan\" must also be developed, with community involvement, and the plan \"should provide for the conservation and enhancement of the byway's intrinsic qualities as well as the promotion of tourism and economic development\". The final step is when the highway (or highways) is approved for designation by the [[Secretary of Transportation]].<ref name=policy />\n\n===Colorado history===\nThe path of I-70 in Colorado is derived from two previous highways, [[U.S. Route 6 in Colorado|US&nbsp;6]] and [[U.S. Route 40 in Colorado|US&nbsp;40]]. US&nbsp;40 was an original piece of the [[U.S. Highway]] system commissioned in 1926. The portion now numbered US&nbsp;6 came about in 1937 when the route over [[Vail Pass]] was paved. A portion of this route was also numbered [[U.S. Route 24 in Colorado|US&nbsp;24]] at the time.<ref name=broer>{{cite map |publisher=Rand McNally |title=Road Atlas |via=Broer Map Library) |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/Southwest/randmcnally_ra_1946_022.html |year=1946 |page=24 |accessdate=May 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1920s, SH-139 was an unimproved road from US&nbsp;6 at Fruita north to SH-64 in Rangely.<ref>{{cite map |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/NorthernRockies/Colorado/unitedstates1926ra_062.html |publisher=Rand McNally |title=Junior Road Map: Colorado |accessdate=April 25, 2009 |year=1926 |via=Broer Map Library}}</ref>\n\n===Utah history===\n[[Image:HuntSceneNMC.JPG|thumb|right|[[Petroglyph]]s inside [[Nine Mile Canyon]]]]\n\nThe first route through this portion of Utah was the [[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Old Spanish Trail]], a trade route between [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]] and [[Los Angeles, California]]. The trail was in common use before the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in 1848.<ref name=oldspanishtrail>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/trail_history.php |title=Old Spanish Trail History |accessdate=March 19, 2008 |last=von Till Warren |first=Elizabeth |publisher=Old Spanish Trail Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308045310/http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/trail_history.php |archivedate=March 8, 2008 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although the trail serves a different route than I-70, they were both intended to connect southern California with points further east. I-70 generally parallels the route of the Old Spanish Trail west of [[Crescent Junction, Utah|Crescent Junction]].<ref name=oldspanishtrail2>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/maps.php |title=Old Spanish Trail Association: Maps |accessdate=February 28, 2008 |publisher=Old Spanish Trail Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080201122612/http://www.oldspanishtrail.org/maps.php |archivedate=February 1, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Utah State Road Commission]] took over US&nbsp;40 from Kimball Junction to Colorado in 1910 and 1911,<ref name=history-6>{{cite web |publisher=[[Utah Department of Transportation]] |url=http://www.udot.utah.gov/download.php/tid=1348/SR-006.pdf |format=PDF |title=Route 6 history |date=September 2005 |access-date=April 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005120302/http://www2.udot.utah.gov/download.php/tid=1348/SR-006.pdf |archive-date=October 5, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and assigned the SR-6 designation to this route by the mid-1920s.<ref name=\"1926 Rand McNally\">{{cite map |publisher=[[Rand McNally]] |title=Auto Road Atlas |year=1926 |url=http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/ |via=Broer Map Library}}</ref> In late 1926, the [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] (AASHO) assigned the designation of US&nbsp;40 to this cross-state route, consisting of most of SR-4 and all of SR-6.<ref name=\"1926 map\">{{cite map |publisher=[[Bureau of Public Roads]] |title=United States System of Highways Adopted for Uniform Marking by the American Association of State Highway Officials |url=http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth298433/m1/1/zoom/ |date=November 11, 1926 |accessdate=November 7, 2013 |scale=1:7,000,000 |cartography=U.S. Geological Survey |oclc=32889555}}</ref> (The SR-6 designation remained until the [[1977 renumbering (Utah)|1977 renumbering]]; SR-4 became [[Utah State Route 2 (1962-1977)|SR-2]] in 1962 and was eliminated in favor of [[I-80 (UT)|I-80]] in 1977.)\n\nThe road connecting [[Colton, Utah|Colton]] on [[Utah State Route 8 (1920s-1977)|SR-8]] (US&nbsp;50, now US&nbsp;6) with [[Utah State Route 6 (1920s-1977)|SR-6]] (US&nbsp;40) in [[Duchesne, Utah|Duchesne]] became a state highway in 1910. The southwest end was moved from Colton to [[Castle Gate, Utah|Castle Gate]] in 1912<!--include more history of the Emma Park Road here?-->,<ref name=resolutions-33>{{cite web |publisher=[[Utah Department of Transportation]] |work= Highway Resolutions |url=http://www.udot.utah.gov/main/uconowner.gf?n=200609140937301 |title=Route 33 |format=PDF |date=October 2007 |accessdate=May 2008}}</ref> and in 1927 it was numbered State Route 33.<ref>{{cite UTSR law|year=1927|quote=33. From Castle Gate northeasterly to Duchesne.}}</ref> Few changes were made to the roadway, and in 1981 it became part of US&nbsp;191.<ref name=resolutions-33 />\n\nAccess between Moab and Castle Valley was originally via a [[pack trail]] called the Heavenly Stairway. This trail, named for a dramatic descent of over {{convert|1000|ft|m}}, was described as beautiful, but difficult to navigate.<ref name=\"grandmemories\">{{cite book |last=Daughters of Utah Pioneers |authorlink=Daughters of Utah Pioneers |title=Grand Memories |year=1972 |pages=127, 144 |oclc=4790603}}</ref> Isolated from Utah's population centers, this area depended on [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] and other cities in Colorado for both everyday supplies and a market for agricultural products.<ref name=\"utahdotgov\">{{cite web |url=http://history.utah.gov/apps/markers/detailed_results.php?markerid=2944 |title=Utah History Resource Center: Markers and Monuments, Dewey Bridge |date=October 2006 |accessdate=October 13, 2007 |publisher=State of Utah |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121214152409/http://history.utah.gov/apps/markers/detailed_results.php?markerid=2944 |archivedate=December 14, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Moab residents pushed for a road to be built along the riverbank. By 1902, the trail was replaced with a toll road, called King's Toll Road, after Samuel King. King was an early settler who also operated the toll [[ferry]] used prior to the construction of the [[Dewey Bridge]]. Rocks inscribed with \"Kings Toll Road\" can still be found along the roadway. While the road did improve travel, it was not built high enough above the river level and was often flooded.<ref name=\"grandmemories\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|U.S. Roads|Colorado|Utah}}\n* [[Grand Mesa Scenic and Historic Byway]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway}}\n* [http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/byways/2474 Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway], Federal Highway Administration\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111113154915/http://dinosaurdiamond.org/ Dinosaur Diamond Scenic Byway at dinosaurdiamond.org] - via the Wayback Machine\n* [http://www.utah.com/byways/dinosaur_diamond.htm Dinosaur Diamond Prehistoric Highway], Utah Office of Tourism\n\n[[Category:National Scenic Byways in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Utah Scenic Byways]]\n[[Category:Colorado Scenic Byways]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Carbon County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Duchesne County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Grand County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Emery County, Utah|Transportation in Emery County]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Moffat County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Rio Blanco County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Garfield County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Mesa County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Carbon County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Duchesne County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Grand County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Emery County, Utah|Visitor attractions in Emery County]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Moffat County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Rio Blanco County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Garfield County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Mesa County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Interstate 70]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 6]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 40]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 50]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Utah]]\n", "name_user": "An Errant Knight", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/